{"repo": "automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine", "pull_number": 419, "instance_id": "automatic-ripping-machine__automatic-ripping-machine-419", "issue_numbers": [1170], "base_commit": "1a107e4abbb072e05aa5060f62ee7dcaef22eca1", "patch": "diff --git a/arm/ripper/identify.py b/arm/ripper/identify.py\nindex 4bb8b02f9..35f153424 100644\n--- a/arm/ripper/identify.py\n+++ b/arm/ripper/identify.py\n@@ -167,6 +167,7 @@ def identify_dvd(job):\n     except pydvdid.exceptions.PydvdidException as e:\n         logging.error(\"Pydvdid failed with the error: \" + str(e))\n         dvd_title = fallback_title = str(job.label)\n+        crc64 = \"\"\n \n     logging.info(\"DVD CRC64 hash is: \" + str(crc64))\n     job.crc_id = str(crc64)\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "\ud83d\udc0b Container is stuck in status \"health: starting\" when running inside an ipv6 network\n### Is there an existing issue for this?\n\n- [X] I have searched the existing issues\n\n### Does this issue exist in the latest version?\n\n- [X] I'm using the latest release\n\n### Describe the bug?\n\nWhen I start the container in an ipv6 enabled docker network, it's stuck in `health: starting`. A.R.M. is starting normally as far as I can tell and the UI is accessible though.\r\n\r\nI stumbled across this because I'm running arm behind a traefik reverse proxy (for internal network only), so the proxy network from the provided example compose file is an external network in my case. I need the container to be on that network so traefik can reach it. This is a problem because traefik only starts to pick up containers once they are in health status `running`.\r\n\r\nI also noticed that inside the container the binding on port `8080` is not on `localhost` but on the ip on the docker network (for example `172.29.0.2`). Could that be related? That stopped me from just setting a custom healthcheck inside of my docker compose file, because I can't simply curl localhost.\n\n### To Reproduce\n\n```\r\nservices:\r\n  arm:\r\n    container_name: arm\r\n    image: automaticrippingmachine/automatic-ripping-machine:2.7.2\r\n    restart: unless-stopped\r\n    privileged: true\r\n    environment:\r\n      - ARM_UID=110\r\n      - ARM_GID=110\r\n      - AUTH_TYPE=Basic\r\n    devices:\r\n      - /dev/sr0:/dev/sr0\r\n    ports:\r\n      - 8080:8080\r\n    networks:\r\n      - proxy\r\n\r\nnetworks:\r\n  proxy:\r\n    name: proxy\r\n    enable_ipv6: true\r\n```\n\n### Built from source files ?\n\n- [ ] I Built the image from source\n\n### What architecture are you seeing the problem on?\n\namd64\n\n### Expected behavior?\n\nThe container should leave status `starting` and enter status `running`\n\n### Relevant log output\n\n_No response_\n\n### Anything else?\n\n_No response_\n\n### Code of Conduct\n\n- [X] I agree to follow this project's Code of Conduct\n", "hints_text": "\n\n", "all_hints_text": "If youre having issues, please remember to read the [wiki](https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/wiki/FAQ) and follow the instructions carefully\nThanks for trying ARM, can you provide details from the docker logs. Something like `docker logs -f automatic-ripping-machine `, using the name of your ARM container.\r\n\r\nDocker uses a network bridge to loop back to the local machine, and some docker network magic. Not having tested ARM or even docker with ipv6, I can't say much on what would happen.\r\nHowever, provide any logs you do get, as well as the `docker ps` and go from there\nAs a workaroud you can set a healthcheck, just like I already tried. Instead of using localhost use the name of your container, like this:\n\n```\nhealthcheck:\n      test: curl --fail http://arm:8080 || exit 1\n      interval: 60s\n      retries: 2\n      start_period: 20s\n      timeout: 10\n```\nNot quite sure how you have setup your machine, I can see you have an ipv6 network, but is it assigning an ipv6 address to ARM?\r\nA quite look at [Docker ipv6](https://docs.docker.com/engine/daemon/ipv6/), shows it as possible, with docker providing address for both ipv4 and ipv6.\r\n\r\nNot having done any work with ipv6 and docker I am not able to provide much help.\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/commit/c92c1b7b4b87078f0522b1a82f938b592e0afe3a"], "created_at": "2021-03-28T07:56:44Z"}
{"repo": "automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine", "pull_number": 1302, "instance_id": "automatic-ripping-machine__automatic-ripping-machine-1302", "issue_numbers": [1299], "base_commit": "e53fb7ed26fc63590c165dbbc03310f871b367b8", "patch": "diff --git a/VERSION b/VERSION\nindex 8392a795a..e6cb6a1ae 100644\n--- a/VERSION\n+++ b/VERSION\n@@ -1,1 +1,1 @@\n-2.21.2\n+2.21.3\ndiff --git a/arm/ripper/makemkv.py b/arm/ripper/makemkv.py\nindex 181cbc1ca..49493a61e 100644\n--- a/arm/ripper/makemkv.py\n+++ b/arm/ripper/makemkv.py\n@@ -594,7 +594,7 @@ def makemkv_info(job, select=None, index=9999, options=None):\n     if not isinstance(options, list):\n         raise TypeError(options)\n     # 1MB cache size to get info on the specified disc(s)\n-    info_options = [\"info\", \"--cache=1\"] + options + [f\"disc:{index:d}\"]\n+    info_options = [\"info\", \"--cache=1\"] + options + [f\"disc:{index:d}\", \"--minlength=0\"]\n     wait_time = job.config.MANUAL_WAIT_TIME\n     max_processes = job.config.MAX_CONCURRENT_MAKEMKVINFO\n     job.status = JobState.VIDEO_WAITING.value\n@@ -829,6 +829,7 @@ def process_single_tracks(job, rawpath, mode: str):\n             ]\n             cmd += shlex.split(job.config.MKV_ARGS)\n             cmd += [\n+                f\"--minlength={job.config.MINLENGTH}\",\n                 f\"--progress={progress_log(job)}\",\n                 f\"dev:{job.devpath}\",\n                 track.track_number,\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "\ud83d\udc1b MINLENGTH not respected, always 120\n### Is there an existing issue for this?\n\n- [x] I have searched the existing issues\n\n### I have checked the wiki\n\n- [x] I have searched the wiki for this problem\n\n### Does this issue exist in the latest version?\n\n- [x] I'm using the latest release\n\n### Describe the bug?\n\nThe MINLENGTH and MAXLENGTH are not being applied properly.\n\nThe target track is 68 seconds, and so a range of 30~110 seconds should easily capture it.\nBut instead the track is skipped and not ripped.\n\n\n\n### To Reproduce\n\n1. Set MINLENGTH to 30 seconds (less than desired track time)\n\nConfig:\n```\ngrep LENGTH /arm/config/arm.yaml \nMINLENGTH: 30\nMAXLENGTH: 110\n```\n\n2. Rip the DVD\n\n### What OS are you seeing the problem on?\n\nOther (please state in Anything else? section)\n\n### ARM Release Version or Git hash (You can find this in the arm settings page)\n\nA.R.M version: 2.10.5\nCurrent git version: 1ce96f3\n\n### Expected behavior?\n\n68 second track should have been ripped\n\n### Relevant log output\n\n```shell\nLog excerpt:\n\ngrep 68 /arm/logs/Schoolhouse_Rock_Disc2_173881926303.log \n[02-06-2025 05:21:03] INFO ARM: Alembic head is: 6870a5546912\n[02-06-2025 05:21:03] INFO ARM: Database version is: 6870a5546912\nMSG:3025,16777216,3,\"Title #20 has length of 68 seconds which is less than minimum title length of 120 seconds and was therefore skipped\",\"Title #%1 has length of %2 seconds which is less than minimum title length of %3 seconds and was therefore skipped\",\"20\",\"68\",\"120\"\n[02-06-2025 05:37:21] INFO ARM: Processing track #17 of 30. Length is 68 seconds.\nMSG:3025,16777216,3,\"Title #20 has length of 68 seconds which is less than minimum title length of 120 seconds and was therefore skipped\",\"Title #%1 has length of %2 seconds which is less than minimum title length of %3 seconds and was therefore skipped\",\"20\",\"68\",\"120\"\nMSG:3025,0,3,\"Title #20 has length of 68 seconds which is less than minimum title length of 120 seconds and was therefore skipped\",\"Title #%1 has length of %2 seconds which is less than minimum title length of %3 seconds and was therefore skipped\",\"20\",\"68\",\"120\"\n```\n\n### Anything else?\n\nUbuntu 22.04.5\n\n### Code of Conduct\n\n- [x] I agree to follow this project's Code of Conduct\n", "hints_text": "ARM does respect the min length but only in certain instances.\n1. With 'RIPMETHOD' set to 'backup' or 'backup_dvd', that or if ARM auto-detects that the disk is a bluray. The min length value gets passed to makeMKV.\n2. With 'MAINFEATURE' set to 'False' and the drive rip method set to 'Manual', you can manually select which track you want ARM to rip from a DVD or Bluray.\n\nAgree though that this is confusing, we are working on making the settings easier to understand in Rev 3.x (slowly)\nAh, fascinating!\nThank you very much.\n\nSo I guess this behavior change was introduced with v2.10, is that right?\nI know I have used this method in the past, and I have been using RIPMETHOD=mkv for ages.\n\nAnyway, I would like to ask some further clarifying questions, please.\nRegarding:\n\n> With 'RIPMETHOD' set to 'backup' or 'backup_dvd', ...\n\nThe information dialog for RIPMETHOD says:\n\n> Method of MakeMKV to use for Blu Ray discs.\n\nAre you saying that RIPMETHOD modulates DVD ripping behavior also?\n\nAnd for:\n\n> drive rip method set to 'Manual', you can manually select which track you want ARM to rip from a DVD or Bluray.\n\nThis is amazing!\nI have been doing this the hard way, thank you very much!\nI wonder how long this has been available, lol.\n\nFor anyone else, this is described here:\nhttps://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/wiki/Web-Jobs\nHello again,\nI'm afraid I still can't get the desired track to rip.\nFrom the following information:\n\n> 1. With 'RIPMETHOD' set to 'backup' or 'backup_dvd', that or if ARM auto-detects that the disk is a bluray. The min length value gets passed to makeMKV.\n> 2. With 'MAINFEATURE' set to 'False' and the drive rip method set to 'Manual', you can manually select which track you want ARM to rip from a DVD or Bluray.\n\nI have tried multiple combinations, and none of them have produced the desired file.\nAll are MAINFEATURE false\n| RIPMETHOD | Drive Method | Result |\n| --- | ---| --- |\n| mkv | auto | Ends with error, wrong raw file(s) |\n| mkv | manual | Ends with error, wrong raw file(s) |\n| backup | auto | Ends with no file |\n| backup | manual | Ends with no file (note that it proceeded as if in auto) |\n| backup_dvd | auto | Ends with no file, wrong raw file(s) |\n| backup_dvd | manual | Ends with error, wrong raw file(s) |\n\nNote that I am ripping from DVD.\n\nLooking in the makemkv.py file, I'm not so sure the described conditions for passing MINLENGTH are accurate?\n\nI see 6 mkvcon commands...\n\n`def makemkv(logfile, job):`\n**1**\n```\n    # confirm MKV is working, beta key hasn't expired\n    cmd = f\"makemkvcon -r info disc:9999 | grep {job.devpath} | grep -oP '(?<=:).*?(?=,)'\"\n```\n--minlength absent (not necessary)\n\n**2**\n```\n    # Rip bluray\n    if (job.config.RIPMETHOD == \"backup\" or job.config.RIPMETHOD == \"backup_dvd\") and job.disctype == \"bluray\":\n        # backup method\n        cmd = f'makemkvcon backup --decrypt {job.config.MKV_ARGS} --minlength={job.config.MINLENGTH}' \\\n              f'--progress={os.path.join(job.config.LOGPATH, \"progress\", str(job.job_id))}.log ' \\\n              f'--messages=-stdout ' \\\n              f'-r disc:{mdisc.strip()} {shlex.quote(rawpath)}'\n```\n--minlength present, but also requires job.disctype == \"bluray\"\n\n**3**\n```\n        # if no maximum length, process the whole disc in one command\n        elif int(job.config.MAXLENGTH) > 99998:\n            cmd = f'makemkvcon mkv {job.config.MKV_ARGS} -r ' \\\n                  f'--progress={os.path.join(job.config.LOGPATH, \"progress\", str(job.job_id))}.log ' \\\n                  f'--messages=-stdout ' \\\n                  f'dev:{job.devpath} all {shlex.quote(rawpath)} --minlength={job.config.MINLENGTH}'\n```\n--minlength present, but also requires MAXLENGTH > 99998\n\n`def rip_mainfeature(job, track, logfile, rawpath):`\n**4**\n```\n    cmd = f'makemkvcon mkv {job.config.MKV_ARGS} -r' \\\n          f' --progress={os.path.join(job.config.LOGPATH, \"progress\", str(job.job_id))}.log' \\\n          f' --messages=-stdout ' \\\n          f'dev:{job.devpath} {track.track_number} {shlex.quote(rawpath)} ' \\\n          f'--minlength={job.config.MINLENGTH}'\n```\n--minlength present, but only called if job.config.MAINFEATURE\n\n`def process_single_tracks(job, logfile, rawpath, mode: str):`\n**5**\n```\n        # Rip the track if the user has set it to rip, or in auto mode and the time is good\n        if track.process:\n            logging.info(f\"Processing track #{track.track_number} of {(job.no_of_titles - 1)}. \"\n                         f\"Length is {track.length} seconds.\")\n            filepathname = os.path.join(rawpath, track.filename)\n            logging.info(f\"Ripping title {track.track_number} to {shlex.quote(filepathname)}\")\n\n            cmd = f'makemkvcon mkv {job.config.MKV_ARGS} -r ' \\\n                  f'--progress={os.path.join(job.config.LOGPATH, \"progress\", str(job.job_id))}.log ' \\\n                  f'--messages=-stdout ' \\\n                  f'dev:{job.devpath} {track.track_number} {shlex.quote(rawpath)}'\n```\n--minlength absent\n_Why? Is there any reason to exclude --minlength here?_\n\n`def get_track_info(mdisc, job):`\n**6**\n```\n    cmd = f'makemkvcon -r --progress={os.path.join(job.config.LOGPATH, \"progress\", str(job.job_id))}.log ' \\\n          f'--messages=-stdout --minlength={job.config.MINLENGTH} ' \\\n          f'--cache=1 info disc:{mdisc}'\n```\n--minlength present\n\n\n> ```\n>         # Rip the track if the user has set it to rip, or in auto mode and the time is good\n>         if track.process:\n>             logging.info(f\"Processing track #{track.track_number} of {(job.no_of_titles - 1)}. \"\n>                          f\"Length is {track.length} seconds.\")\n>             filepathname = os.path.join(rawpath, track.filename)\n>             logging.info(f\"Ripping title {track.track_number} to {shlex.quote(filepathname)}\")\n> \n>             cmd = f'makemkvcon mkv {job.config.MKV_ARGS} -r ' \\\n>                   f'--progress={os.path.join(job.config.LOGPATH, \"progress\", str(job.job_id))}.log ' \\\n>                   f'--messages=-stdout ' \\\n>                   f'dev:{job.devpath} {track.track_number} {shlex.quote(rawpath)}'\n> ```\n> \n> --minlength absent\n> _Why? Is there any reason to exclude --minlength here?_\n> \n\nFound when it was removed, 2024/11/10 from commit d087730\n\nGood, I'm not crazy. I knew the behavior used to be different!  \ud83d\ude05\n> `def process_single_tracks(job, logfile, rawpath, mode: str):` **5**\n> \n> ```\n>         # Rip the track if the user has set it to rip, or in auto mode and the time is good\n>         if track.process:\n>             logging.info(f\"Processing track #{track.track_number} of {(job.no_of_titles - 1)}. \"\n>                          f\"Length is {track.length} seconds.\")\n>             filepathname = os.path.join(rawpath, track.filename)\n>             logging.info(f\"Ripping title {track.track_number} to {shlex.quote(filepathname)}\")\n> \n>             cmd = f'makemkvcon mkv {job.config.MKV_ARGS} -r ' \\\n>                   f'--progress={os.path.join(job.config.LOGPATH, \"progress\", str(job.job_id))}.log ' \\\n>                   f'--messages=-stdout ' \\\n>                   f'dev:{job.devpath} {track.track_number} {shlex.quote(rawpath)}'\n> ```\n> \n> --minlength absent _Why? Is there any reason to exclude --minlength here?_\n\nI can't test it right now due to an outdated MakeMKV, but at first glance this makes sense?\n\n* When the user manually selects a title, setting a min-length makes no sense because it would potentially contradict the selection and not rip it because it's too short - despite explicit selection by the user\n* If the comment is to be believed, this function is also called in auto mode, but only *after* the tracks have already been selected (including min-length), so there's no reason to pass it here *again*. If the track was shorter then min-length, it wouldn't even reach this function in the first place, no?\n\nedit:\nChecked the context of that code, and yes, it wouldn't reach that without passing `MINLENGTH` and `MAXLENGTH` first:\n\nhttps://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/blob/1ce96f3f95b1e6a83f42af32af503c3f3bda1872/arm/ripper/makemkv.py#L135-L175\n\nNote lines 148 and 154 specifically (and by extension 160-162). It checks for `MIN` and `MAX` first, and only if it's between the two it sets `track.process = True` and goes on to actually process the track. Passing the length again would not add any benefit here because tracks below `MIN` are never processed in the first place.\n\n***However:*** I don't see anything here that would force the rip with a manual selection. It checks for `mode == 'auto'` in L147, but it doesn't handle any case where it's *not* `auto` (i.e. `manual`), and the `track.process` condition doesn't check it either.\nBut the manual rip might be handled elsewhere, I haven't read it all.\n\nedit edit:\nOne thing to consider is how MakeMKV itself handles the minimum duration when a track was explicitly selected, which would have to be tested.\nIt might be that the issue here is not actually ARM, but rather MakeMKV itself. I can't test this right now but at its core I think the question is:\nDoes MakeMKV impose either its own default `minlength` or even a supplied `--minlength` when a track was explicitly selected for ripping?\nIMO MakeMKV should ignore both its default *and* `--minlength` if a track was explicitly selected. It should only use a minimum length for auto-selection (because otherwise what's the point of manual selection?).\n*If* it enforces the min-length regardless of manual selection, we'd have to *always* pass `--minlength=0` because otherwise we could run into conflicts with manual selection. And automatic selection is already handled through the `if elif else` construct cited above.\n\n---\n\nThat being said, can you post your MakeMKV config? I have a hunch. Delete the `app_Key` if present and you have a permakey.\n```sh\n# from within the container if using Docker\n$ cat /home/arm/.MakeMKV/settings.conf\n```\nYour points make good intuitive sense, however the critical thing is that makemkv uses a default of 120 seconds minimum.\nYou were right on the money with this speculation:\n\n> If it enforces the min-length regardless of manual selection, we'd have to always pass --minlength=0 because otherwise we could run into conflicts with manual selection.\n\nThis is precisely the problem.\n\n> And automatic selection is already handled through the if elif else construct cited above.\n\nBut unfortunately makemkv skips over anything < 120 _unless --minlength argument is passed_.\nSo although 100 s (for example) gets properly handled by said construct, makemkv still skips it.\n\nThis is very confusing in auto mode.\nBut it is even more frustrating in manual mode (as you suggested)!\nBecause:\n1. The user is presented with options to choose from that properly respect MINLENGTH\nThis is because get_track_info() includes --minlength argument\n```\n    cmd = f'makemkvcon -r --progress={os.path.join(job.config.LOGPATH, \"progress\", str(job.job_id))}.log ' \\\n          f'--messages=-stdout --minlength={job.config.MINLENGTH} ' \\\n          f'--cache=1 info disc:{mdisc}'\n```\n\n2. But then if any of the selected options are <120s they don't get ripped by makemkv!\nThis is because process_single_tracks() does not include --minlength argument\n```\n            cmd = f'makemkvcon mkv {job.config.MKV_ARGS} -r ' \\\n                  f'--progress={os.path.join(job.config.LOGPATH, \"progress\", str(job.job_id))}.log ' \\\n                  f'--messages=-stdout ' \\\n                  f'dev:{job.devpath} {track.track_number} {shlex.quote(rawpath)}'\n```\nSo without the argument, makemkv uses its own minlength 120 default\nSee related Issue #1301\n\n> IMO MakeMKV should ignore both its default and --minlength if a track was explicitly selected. It should only use a minimum length for auto-selection (because otherwise what's the point of manual selection?).\n\nNo argument here.\nThis behavior seems to surprise a lot of people (myself included), the makemkv forums have multiple hits on this topic.\n\n\n> That being said, can you post your MakeMKV config? I have a hunch. Delete the app_Key if present and you have a permakey.\n\n```\ncat /home/arm/.MakeMKV/settings.conf \napp_Key = \"M-zF4mzZhlv0BwBvhNDcT@6lfzi_6sW7erm67ba7veWz5woE1w7mSYTSPPWqP1eY8oyC\"\n```\n\nI do have a permakey, but I don't observe any problems there.\nMy patch has resolved my problem and I don't want to change anything right now since I currently have a rip in progress, so I can follow up on this later if needed.\n> Your points make good intuitive sense, however the critical thing is that makemkv uses a default of 120 seconds minimum. You were right on the money with this speculation:\n> \n> > If it enforces the min-length regardless of manual selection, we'd have to always pass --minlength=0 because otherwise we could run into conflicts with manual selection.\n> \n> This is precisely the problem.\n> \n> > And automatic selection is already handled through the if elif else construct cited above.\n> \n> But unfortunately makemkv skips over anything < 120 _unless --minlength argument is passed_. So although 100 s (for example) gets properly handled by said construct, makemkv still skips it.\n\nOK then IMHO that is a bug with MakeMKV and should be reported there.\nWe can of course work around it, but this being default behaviour is bad. It goes against explicit user selection which makes the entire manual selection process that `makemkvcon` provides obsolete (not only through ARM, but `makemkvcon` in general).\nThis is especially annoying because the [`usage.txt`](https://www.makemkv.com/developers/usage.txt#:~:text=decryption.%0A%0AConversion%20options%3A-,%2D%2Dminlength%3Dseconds,-Specify%20minimum%20title) makes no mention of this:\n> --minlength=seconds\n> Specify minimum title length. Default: program preferences.\n\nAs noted above though, the `--minlength` should probably be forced to `0` for the aforementioned reasons, and/or that `if elif else` block needs to handle `manual` mode. The function expects a `mode` parameter, but that is only used to check for `auto`.\nedit:\nActually, checking #1301 it seems MakeMKV is numbering tracks differently depending on the `--minlength` as well... I thought it would assign the track numbers and names first, and then filter for the `--minlength` (which is what the GUI does AFAIK), but it seems it's the opposite way. So it seems `0` is out the window. Shouldn't make a difference though when the same `MINLENGTH` is passed to both.\nI'm just perplexed how the `manual` mode works at all in the first place. `if track.process` should never evaluate true in `manual` mode? It's undefined before L145 and since `mode` is (presumably) not `auto`, it should never be set to `true`\u2026 and I don't see it being passed as part of `job` either.\n\n---\n\n> So without the argument, makemkv uses its own minlength 120 default See related Issue [#1301](https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/issues/1301)\n\n> ```\n> cat /home/arm/.MakeMKV/settings.conf \n> app_Key = \"M-zF4mzZhlv0BwBvhNDcT@6lfzi_6sW7erm67ba7veWz5woE1w7mSYTSPPWqP1eY8oyC\"\n> ```\n\nWhich is another issue. The `usage.txt` (see above) says \"program preferences\", however this is:\n- Not a preference the user set - when setting this in the GUI, it is saved under the `dvd_MinimumTitleLength` key, as mentioned [in the Wiki](https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/wiki/MakeMKV-Info#settingsconf:~:text=dvd_MinimumTitleLength).\n- Not mentioned in the `usage.txt` whatsoever. It's something the user can infer when they have used the MakeMKV GUI before and happened to see the value in the config dialogue, however it's impossible to know without having used it.\n- Not logged by `makemkvcon` so that the user is informed a default value is being used and can be overwritten\n- I guess *technically* a \"program preference\" because the program\u2026 prefers the default value.\n\nTakeaway: using the `dvd_MinimumTitleLength` with a preferred minimum length value should also work\nThank you both, there has been some good discussion and investigation. I am by no means a MakeMKV expert. The change I made removed the min length to avoid issues with a manual job failing due to a min length of say 300 seconds if the user wanted a smaller file; not aware of the 120 second minimum.\n\nWith regards to the update, agree that the option should not conflict with a user selection when in auto or manual. Adding the min length back in as in #1302 will cause that confusion.\n\nI am happy for a patch to be added in for v2.x, and we can resolve the correct flow in v3.x this year. I will raise a new issue for v3.x issues as a build fix in the new version of ARM, and add this issue.\n> With regards to the update, agree that the option should not conflict with a user selection when in auto or manual. Adding the min length back in as in [#1302](https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/pull/1302) will cause that confusion.\n\nLooking at the logs in #1301 I don't think it would.\nIt seems that when in manual mode, listing the titles is already using the `MINLENGTH` (as it should) and it seems that MakeMKV sets the title numbers and filenames *after* filtering by length.\nWhen then going on to actually ripping, those numbers and names are seemingly only preserved when *also* passing `MINLENGTH`. It seems that `makemkvcon` doesn't save states between calls (as opposed to MakeMKV GUI because the selection is saved in the GUI, not the ripper), so not passing `MINLENGTH` results in different title numbers and filenames.\nAnd since both calls use the same `MINLENGTH`, there shouldn't be a situation where a title is selectable but then discarded during ripping, i.e. a user wouldn't be able to choose a title that couldn't be ripped in the first place.\nThere is a fair bit of detailed discussion above, but I have been seeing rip failures related to this and only after reading the whole thread and investigating thoroughly realised this is the cause. So for the reference of future users, here is a summary of the failure conditions:\n\nUnder these conditions a rip will fail:\n- `MINLENGTH` less than `120`\n- `MAXLENGTH` set to any value greater than `MINLENGTH`\n- Disc being ripped my MakeMKV\n- Ripped disc includes tracks which are greater than `MINLENGTH` and less than `120`\n\n**Workaround**\n\nRemove your `MAXLENGTH` or set your `MINLENGTH` to 120 or above.\n\n*If you require titles which are less than 120 seconds, the only way to rip these successfully is to remove your `MAXLENGTH`.*\n\n", "all_hints_text": "ARM does respect the min length but only in certain instances.\n1. With 'RIPMETHOD' set to 'backup' or 'backup_dvd', that or if ARM auto-detects that the disk is a bluray. The min length value gets passed to makeMKV.\n2. With 'MAINFEATURE' set to 'False' and the drive rip method set to 'Manual', you can manually select which track you want ARM to rip from a DVD or Bluray.\n\nAgree though that this is confusing, we are working on making the settings easier to understand in Rev 3.x (slowly)\nAh, fascinating!\nThank you very much.\n\nSo I guess this behavior change was introduced with v2.10, is that right?\nI know I have used this method in the past, and I have been using RIPMETHOD=mkv for ages.\n\nAnyway, I would like to ask some further clarifying questions, please.\nRegarding:\n\n> With 'RIPMETHOD' set to 'backup' or 'backup_dvd', ...\n\nThe information dialog for RIPMETHOD says:\n\n> Method of MakeMKV to use for Blu Ray discs.\n\nAre you saying that RIPMETHOD modulates DVD ripping behavior also?\n\nAnd for:\n\n> drive rip method set to 'Manual', you can manually select which track you want ARM to rip from a DVD or Bluray.\n\nThis is amazing!\nI have been doing this the hard way, thank you very much!\nI wonder how long this has been available, lol.\n\nFor anyone else, this is described here:\nhttps://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/wiki/Web-Jobs\nHello again,\nI'm afraid I still can't get the desired track to rip.\nFrom the following information:\n\n> 1. With 'RIPMETHOD' set to 'backup' or 'backup_dvd', that or if ARM auto-detects that the disk is a bluray. The min length value gets passed to makeMKV.\n> 2. With 'MAINFEATURE' set to 'False' and the drive rip method set to 'Manual', you can manually select which track you want ARM to rip from a DVD or Bluray.\n\nI have tried multiple combinations, and none of them have produced the desired file.\nAll are MAINFEATURE false\n| RIPMETHOD | Drive Method | Result |\n| --- | ---| --- |\n| mkv | auto | Ends with error, wrong raw file(s) |\n| mkv | manual | Ends with error, wrong raw file(s) |\n| backup | auto | Ends with no file |\n| backup | manual | Ends with no file (note that it proceeded as if in auto) |\n| backup_dvd | auto | Ends with no file, wrong raw file(s) |\n| backup_dvd | manual | Ends with error, wrong raw file(s) |\n\nNote that I am ripping from DVD.\n\nLooking in the makemkv.py file, I'm not so sure the described conditions for passing MINLENGTH are accurate?\n\nI see 6 mkvcon commands...\n\n`def makemkv(logfile, job):`\n**1**\n```\n    # confirm MKV is working, beta key hasn't expired\n    cmd = f\"makemkvcon -r info disc:9999 | grep {job.devpath} | grep -oP '(?<=:).*?(?=,)'\"\n```\n--minlength absent (not necessary)\n\n**2**\n```\n    # Rip bluray\n    if (job.config.RIPMETHOD == \"backup\" or job.config.RIPMETHOD == \"backup_dvd\") and job.disctype == \"bluray\":\n        # backup method\n        cmd = f'makemkvcon backup --decrypt {job.config.MKV_ARGS} --minlength={job.config.MINLENGTH}' \\\n              f'--progress={os.path.join(job.config.LOGPATH, \"progress\", str(job.job_id))}.log ' \\\n              f'--messages=-stdout ' \\\n              f'-r disc:{mdisc.strip()} {shlex.quote(rawpath)}'\n```\n--minlength present, but also requires job.disctype == \"bluray\"\n\n**3**\n```\n        # if no maximum length, process the whole disc in one command\n        elif int(job.config.MAXLENGTH) > 99998:\n            cmd = f'makemkvcon mkv {job.config.MKV_ARGS} -r ' \\\n                  f'--progress={os.path.join(job.config.LOGPATH, \"progress\", str(job.job_id))}.log ' \\\n                  f'--messages=-stdout ' \\\n                  f'dev:{job.devpath} all {shlex.quote(rawpath)} --minlength={job.config.MINLENGTH}'\n```\n--minlength present, but also requires MAXLENGTH > 99998\n\n`def rip_mainfeature(job, track, logfile, rawpath):`\n**4**\n```\n    cmd = f'makemkvcon mkv {job.config.MKV_ARGS} -r' \\\n          f' --progress={os.path.join(job.config.LOGPATH, \"progress\", str(job.job_id))}.log' \\\n          f' --messages=-stdout ' \\\n          f'dev:{job.devpath} {track.track_number} {shlex.quote(rawpath)} ' \\\n          f'--minlength={job.config.MINLENGTH}'\n```\n--minlength present, but only called if job.config.MAINFEATURE\n\n`def process_single_tracks(job, logfile, rawpath, mode: str):`\n**5**\n```\n        # Rip the track if the user has set it to rip, or in auto mode and the time is good\n        if track.process:\n            logging.info(f\"Processing track #{track.track_number} of {(job.no_of_titles - 1)}. \"\n                         f\"Length is {track.length} seconds.\")\n            filepathname = os.path.join(rawpath, track.filename)\n            logging.info(f\"Ripping title {track.track_number} to {shlex.quote(filepathname)}\")\n\n            cmd = f'makemkvcon mkv {job.config.MKV_ARGS} -r ' \\\n                  f'--progress={os.path.join(job.config.LOGPATH, \"progress\", str(job.job_id))}.log ' \\\n                  f'--messages=-stdout ' \\\n                  f'dev:{job.devpath} {track.track_number} {shlex.quote(rawpath)}'\n```\n--minlength absent\n_Why? Is there any reason to exclude --minlength here?_\n\n`def get_track_info(mdisc, job):`\n**6**\n```\n    cmd = f'makemkvcon -r --progress={os.path.join(job.config.LOGPATH, \"progress\", str(job.job_id))}.log ' \\\n          f'--messages=-stdout --minlength={job.config.MINLENGTH} ' \\\n          f'--cache=1 info disc:{mdisc}'\n```\n--minlength present\n\n\n> ```\n>         # Rip the track if the user has set it to rip, or in auto mode and the time is good\n>         if track.process:\n>             logging.info(f\"Processing track #{track.track_number} of {(job.no_of_titles - 1)}. \"\n>                          f\"Length is {track.length} seconds.\")\n>             filepathname = os.path.join(rawpath, track.filename)\n>             logging.info(f\"Ripping title {track.track_number} to {shlex.quote(filepathname)}\")\n> \n>             cmd = f'makemkvcon mkv {job.config.MKV_ARGS} -r ' \\\n>                   f'--progress={os.path.join(job.config.LOGPATH, \"progress\", str(job.job_id))}.log ' \\\n>                   f'--messages=-stdout ' \\\n>                   f'dev:{job.devpath} {track.track_number} {shlex.quote(rawpath)}'\n> ```\n> \n> --minlength absent\n> _Why? Is there any reason to exclude --minlength here?_\n> \n\nFound when it was removed, 2024/11/10 from commit d087730\n\nGood, I'm not crazy. I knew the behavior used to be different!  \ud83d\ude05\n> `def process_single_tracks(job, logfile, rawpath, mode: str):` **5**\n> \n> ```\n>         # Rip the track if the user has set it to rip, or in auto mode and the time is good\n>         if track.process:\n>             logging.info(f\"Processing track #{track.track_number} of {(job.no_of_titles - 1)}. \"\n>                          f\"Length is {track.length} seconds.\")\n>             filepathname = os.path.join(rawpath, track.filename)\n>             logging.info(f\"Ripping title {track.track_number} to {shlex.quote(filepathname)}\")\n> \n>             cmd = f'makemkvcon mkv {job.config.MKV_ARGS} -r ' \\\n>                   f'--progress={os.path.join(job.config.LOGPATH, \"progress\", str(job.job_id))}.log ' \\\n>                   f'--messages=-stdout ' \\\n>                   f'dev:{job.devpath} {track.track_number} {shlex.quote(rawpath)}'\n> ```\n> \n> --minlength absent _Why? Is there any reason to exclude --minlength here?_\n\nI can't test it right now due to an outdated MakeMKV, but at first glance this makes sense?\n\n* When the user manually selects a title, setting a min-length makes no sense because it would potentially contradict the selection and not rip it because it's too short - despite explicit selection by the user\n* If the comment is to be believed, this function is also called in auto mode, but only *after* the tracks have already been selected (including min-length), so there's no reason to pass it here *again*. If the track was shorter then min-length, it wouldn't even reach this function in the first place, no?\n\nedit:\nChecked the context of that code, and yes, it wouldn't reach that without passing `MINLENGTH` and `MAXLENGTH` first:\n\nhttps://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/blob/1ce96f3f95b1e6a83f42af32af503c3f3bda1872/arm/ripper/makemkv.py#L135-L175\n\nNote lines 148 and 154 specifically (and by extension 160-162). It checks for `MIN` and `MAX` first, and only if it's between the two it sets `track.process = True` and goes on to actually process the track. Passing the length again would not add any benefit here because tracks below `MIN` are never processed in the first place.\n\n***However:*** I don't see anything here that would force the rip with a manual selection. It checks for `mode == 'auto'` in L147, but it doesn't handle any case where it's *not* `auto` (i.e. `manual`), and the `track.process` condition doesn't check it either.\nBut the manual rip might be handled elsewhere, I haven't read it all.\n\nedit edit:\nOne thing to consider is how MakeMKV itself handles the minimum duration when a track was explicitly selected, which would have to be tested.\nIt might be that the issue here is not actually ARM, but rather MakeMKV itself. I can't test this right now but at its core I think the question is:\nDoes MakeMKV impose either its own default `minlength` or even a supplied `--minlength` when a track was explicitly selected for ripping?\nIMO MakeMKV should ignore both its default *and* `--minlength` if a track was explicitly selected. It should only use a minimum length for auto-selection (because otherwise what's the point of manual selection?).\n*If* it enforces the min-length regardless of manual selection, we'd have to *always* pass `--minlength=0` because otherwise we could run into conflicts with manual selection. And automatic selection is already handled through the `if elif else` construct cited above.\n\n---\n\nThat being said, can you post your MakeMKV config? I have a hunch. Delete the `app_Key` if present and you have a permakey.\n```sh\n# from within the container if using Docker\n$ cat /home/arm/.MakeMKV/settings.conf\n```\nYour points make good intuitive sense, however the critical thing is that makemkv uses a default of 120 seconds minimum.\nYou were right on the money with this speculation:\n\n> If it enforces the min-length regardless of manual selection, we'd have to always pass --minlength=0 because otherwise we could run into conflicts with manual selection.\n\nThis is precisely the problem.\n\n> And automatic selection is already handled through the if elif else construct cited above.\n\nBut unfortunately makemkv skips over anything < 120 _unless --minlength argument is passed_.\nSo although 100 s (for example) gets properly handled by said construct, makemkv still skips it.\n\nThis is very confusing in auto mode.\nBut it is even more frustrating in manual mode (as you suggested)!\nBecause:\n1. The user is presented with options to choose from that properly respect MINLENGTH\nThis is because get_track_info() includes --minlength argument\n```\n    cmd = f'makemkvcon -r --progress={os.path.join(job.config.LOGPATH, \"progress\", str(job.job_id))}.log ' \\\n          f'--messages=-stdout --minlength={job.config.MINLENGTH} ' \\\n          f'--cache=1 info disc:{mdisc}'\n```\n\n2. But then if any of the selected options are <120s they don't get ripped by makemkv!\nThis is because process_single_tracks() does not include --minlength argument\n```\n            cmd = f'makemkvcon mkv {job.config.MKV_ARGS} -r ' \\\n                  f'--progress={os.path.join(job.config.LOGPATH, \"progress\", str(job.job_id))}.log ' \\\n                  f'--messages=-stdout ' \\\n                  f'dev:{job.devpath} {track.track_number} {shlex.quote(rawpath)}'\n```\nSo without the argument, makemkv uses its own minlength 120 default\nSee related Issue #1301\n\n> IMO MakeMKV should ignore both its default and --minlength if a track was explicitly selected. It should only use a minimum length for auto-selection (because otherwise what's the point of manual selection?).\n\nNo argument here.\nThis behavior seems to surprise a lot of people (myself included), the makemkv forums have multiple hits on this topic.\n\n\n> That being said, can you post your MakeMKV config? I have a hunch. Delete the app_Key if present and you have a permakey.\n\n```\ncat /home/arm/.MakeMKV/settings.conf \napp_Key = \"M-zF4mzZhlv0BwBvhNDcT@6lfzi_6sW7erm67ba7veWz5woE1w7mSYTSPPWqP1eY8oyC\"\n```\n\nI do have a permakey, but I don't observe any problems there.\nMy patch has resolved my problem and I don't want to change anything right now since I currently have a rip in progress, so I can follow up on this later if needed.\n> Your points make good intuitive sense, however the critical thing is that makemkv uses a default of 120 seconds minimum. You were right on the money with this speculation:\n> \n> > If it enforces the min-length regardless of manual selection, we'd have to always pass --minlength=0 because otherwise we could run into conflicts with manual selection.\n> \n> This is precisely the problem.\n> \n> > And automatic selection is already handled through the if elif else construct cited above.\n> \n> But unfortunately makemkv skips over anything < 120 _unless --minlength argument is passed_. So although 100 s (for example) gets properly handled by said construct, makemkv still skips it.\n\nOK then IMHO that is a bug with MakeMKV and should be reported there.\nWe can of course work around it, but this being default behaviour is bad. It goes against explicit user selection which makes the entire manual selection process that `makemkvcon` provides obsolete (not only through ARM, but `makemkvcon` in general).\nThis is especially annoying because the [`usage.txt`](https://www.makemkv.com/developers/usage.txt#:~:text=decryption.%0A%0AConversion%20options%3A-,%2D%2Dminlength%3Dseconds,-Specify%20minimum%20title) makes no mention of this:\n> --minlength=seconds\n> Specify minimum title length. Default: program preferences.\n\nAs noted above though, the `--minlength` should probably be forced to `0` for the aforementioned reasons, and/or that `if elif else` block needs to handle `manual` mode. The function expects a `mode` parameter, but that is only used to check for `auto`.\nedit:\nActually, checking #1301 it seems MakeMKV is numbering tracks differently depending on the `--minlength` as well... I thought it would assign the track numbers and names first, and then filter for the `--minlength` (which is what the GUI does AFAIK), but it seems it's the opposite way. So it seems `0` is out the window. Shouldn't make a difference though when the same `MINLENGTH` is passed to both.\nI'm just perplexed how the `manual` mode works at all in the first place. `if track.process` should never evaluate true in `manual` mode? It's undefined before L145 and since `mode` is (presumably) not `auto`, it should never be set to `true`\u2026 and I don't see it being passed as part of `job` either.\n\n---\n\n> So without the argument, makemkv uses its own minlength 120 default See related Issue [#1301](https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/issues/1301)\n\n> ```\n> cat /home/arm/.MakeMKV/settings.conf \n> app_Key = \"M-zF4mzZhlv0BwBvhNDcT@6lfzi_6sW7erm67ba7veWz5woE1w7mSYTSPPWqP1eY8oyC\"\n> ```\n\nWhich is another issue. The `usage.txt` (see above) says \"program preferences\", however this is:\n- Not a preference the user set - when setting this in the GUI, it is saved under the `dvd_MinimumTitleLength` key, as mentioned [in the Wiki](https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/wiki/MakeMKV-Info#settingsconf:~:text=dvd_MinimumTitleLength).\n- Not mentioned in the `usage.txt` whatsoever. It's something the user can infer when they have used the MakeMKV GUI before and happened to see the value in the config dialogue, however it's impossible to know without having used it.\n- Not logged by `makemkvcon` so that the user is informed a default value is being used and can be overwritten\n- I guess *technically* a \"program preference\" because the program\u2026 prefers the default value.\n\nTakeaway: using the `dvd_MinimumTitleLength` with a preferred minimum length value should also work\nThank you both, there has been some good discussion and investigation. I am by no means a MakeMKV expert. The change I made removed the min length to avoid issues with a manual job failing due to a min length of say 300 seconds if the user wanted a smaller file; not aware of the 120 second minimum.\n\nWith regards to the update, agree that the option should not conflict with a user selection when in auto or manual. Adding the min length back in as in #1302 will cause that confusion.\n\nI am happy for a patch to be added in for v2.x, and we can resolve the correct flow in v3.x this year. I will raise a new issue for v3.x issues as a build fix in the new version of ARM, and add this issue.\n> With regards to the update, agree that the option should not conflict with a user selection when in auto or manual. Adding the min length back in as in [#1302](https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/pull/1302) will cause that confusion.\n\nLooking at the logs in #1301 I don't think it would.\nIt seems that when in manual mode, listing the titles is already using the `MINLENGTH` (as it should) and it seems that MakeMKV sets the title numbers and filenames *after* filtering by length.\nWhen then going on to actually ripping, those numbers and names are seemingly only preserved when *also* passing `MINLENGTH`. It seems that `makemkvcon` doesn't save states between calls (as opposed to MakeMKV GUI because the selection is saved in the GUI, not the ripper), so not passing `MINLENGTH` results in different title numbers and filenames.\nAnd since both calls use the same `MINLENGTH`, there shouldn't be a situation where a title is selectable but then discarded during ripping, i.e. a user wouldn't be able to choose a title that couldn't be ripped in the first place.\nThere is a fair bit of detailed discussion above, but I have been seeing rip failures related to this and only after reading the whole thread and investigating thoroughly realised this is the cause. So for the reference of future users, here is a summary of the failure conditions:\n\nUnder these conditions a rip will fail:\n- `MINLENGTH` less than `120`\n- `MAXLENGTH` set to any value greater than `MINLENGTH`\n- Disc being ripped my MakeMKV\n- Ripped disc includes tracks which are greater than `MINLENGTH` and less than `120`\n\n**Workaround**\n\nRemove your `MAXLENGTH` or set your `MINLENGTH` to 120 or above.\n\n*If you require titles which are less than 120 seconds, the only way to rip these successfully is to remove your `MAXLENGTH`.*\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/commit/72297f6bcbd8a09d8b03f86543c2c65a0b9eed6f", "https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/commit/90cd1063817dfe6c6b8b764b7fe7a26310eea3f5", "https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/commit/b575527055d514dccf3d385e6a99b1aed8d641ed", "https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/commit/282ec4750ef646fac10a089fc545ab351f81d5d4", "https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/commit/cb71c16e784ec1a1b4384562c3e67508cc8043dc", "https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/commit/2a23efb5def447ff2c65a877833086eb3d0184c1", "https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/commit/6c46b4e0905fa9f3c4e4f90396c22f8c55439934"], "created_at": "2025-02-08T05:35:33Z"}
{"repo": "automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine", "pull_number": 1449, "instance_id": "automatic-ripping-machine__automatic-ripping-machine-1449", "issue_numbers": [1315], "base_commit": "a12437bbd648fe968d755e4346a2af8c1587af1a", "patch": "diff --git a/VERSION b/VERSION\nindex 7329e21c3..0352eb170 100755\n--- a/VERSION\n+++ b/VERSION\n@@ -1,1 +1,1 @@\n-2.20.0\n+2.20.1\n\\ No newline at end of file\ndiff --git a/arm/ripper/music_brainz.py b/arm/ripper/music_brainz.py\nindex 3f1f27a57..4a7be0884 100755\n--- a/arm/ripper/music_brainz.py\n+++ b/arm/ripper/music_brainz.py\n@@ -4,12 +4,12 @@\n import logging\n import re\n import musicbrainzngs as mb\n-import arm.config.config as cfg\n-\n+import werkzeug\n from discid import read, Disc\n \n+import arm.config.config as cfg\n from arm.ripper import utils as u\n-import werkzeug\n+\n \n werkzeug.cached_property = werkzeug.utils.cached_property\n \n@@ -36,109 +36,228 @@ def get_disc_id(disc):\n     return read(disc.devpath)\n \n \n-def music_brainz(discid, job):\n+def music_brainz(discid: str, job) -> str:\n     \"\"\"\n-    Ask musicbrainz.org for the release of the disc\n-    :param discid: identification object from discid package\n-    :param job: the job class/obj\n-    :return: the label of the disc as a string or \"\" if nothing was found\n+    Query MusicBrainz for metadata about an audio disc and update the job with release info.\n+\n+    This function uses the provided disc ID to fetch metadata from MusicBrainz. If successful,\n+    it processes the release or CD stub information and updates the job's database records\n+    with relevant details like artist, album title, and release year.\n+\n+    Parameters\n+    ----------\n+    discid : str\n+        A disc ID string generated by the `discid` package that uniquely identifies an audio CD.\n+    job\n+        A job object that contains metadata and handles logging and database updates.\n+\n+    Returns\n+    -------\n+    str\n+        The label or title of the disc, or an empty string if the disc could not be processed\n+        or no information was found.\n+\n+    Notes\n+    -----\n+    - Calls `get_disc_info()` to retrieve disc metadata from MusicBrainz.\n+    - Uses `check_musicbrainz_data()` to parse and store release data.\n+    - Returns early with an empty string on error.\n+    \"\"\"\n+\n+    disc_info = get_disc_info(job, discid)\n+    if disc_info == \"\":\n+        logging.error(\"ARM has encountered an error and stopping\")\n+        return \"\"\n+\n+    artist_title = check_musicbrainz_data(job, disc_info)\n+    if artist_title == \"\":\n+        logging.error(\"ARM has encountered an error and stopping\")\n+        return \"\"\n+\n+    return artist_title\n+\n+\n+def get_disc_info(job, discid: str) -> str:\n+    \"\"\"\n+    Retrieve CD release information from MusicBrainz using the disc ID.\n+\n+    This function contacts the MusicBrainz web service with a given disc ID\n+    to fetch associated release metadata such as artist credits and recordings.\n+\n+    Parameters\n+    ----------\n+    job\n+        The job object containing configuration, including the ARM version used in the user agent.\n+    discid : str\n+        The disc ID to query in MusicBrainz.\n+\n+    Returns\n+    -------\n+    dict\n+        A dictionary containing release information if successful.\n+        Returns an empty string if an error occurs (e.g., network error, invalid disc ID).\n     \"\"\"\n \n     # Tell musicbrainz what your app is, and how to contact you\n     # (this step is required, as per the webservice access rules\n     # at http://wiki.musicbrainz.org/XML_Web_Service/Rate_Limiting )\n     mb.set_useragent(app=\"arm\", version=str(job.arm_version), contact=\"https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine\")\n+\n+    # Get CD info from musicbrainz and catch any errors\n     try:\n-        infos = mb.get_releases_by_discid(discid, includes=['artist-credits', 'recordings'])\n-        logging.debug(f\"Infos: {infos}\")\n-        logging.debug(f\"discid = {discid}\")\n-        if 'disc' in infos:\n-            process_tracks(job, infos['disc']['release-list'][0]['medium-list'][0]['track-list'])\n-            logging.debug(\"-\" * 300)\n-            release = infos['disc']['release-list'][0]\n-            new_year = check_date(release)\n-            title = str(release.get('title', 'no title'))\n-            # Set out release id as the CRC_ID\n-            args = {\n-                'job_id': str(job.job_id),\n-                'crc_id': release['id'],\n-                'hasnicetitle': True,\n-                'year': str(new_year),\n-                'year_auto': str(new_year),\n-                'title': title,\n-                'title_auto': title\n-            }\n-            u.database_updater(args, job)\n-            logging.debug(f\"musicbrain works -  New title is {title}  New Year is: {new_year}\")\n-        elif 'cdstub' in infos:\n-            process_tracks(job, infos['cdstub']['track-list'], is_stub=True)\n-            title = str(infos['cdstub']['title'])\n-            args = {\n-                'job_id': str(job.job_id),\n-                'crc_id': infos['cdstub']['id'],\n-                'hasnicetitle': True,\n-                'title': title,\n-                'title_auto': title\n-            }\n-            u.database_updater(args, job)\n-            logging.debug(f\"musicbrain works, but stubbed -  New title is {title}\")\n-            if 'artist' in infos['cdstub']:\n-                artist = infos['cdstub']['artist']\n-                args = {\n-                    'job_id': str(job.job_id),\n-                    'crc_id': infos['cdstub']['id'],\n-                    'hasnicetitle': True,\n-                    'title': artist + \" \" + title,\n-                    'title_auto': artist + \" \" + title\n-                }\n-                u.database_updater(args, job)\n+        disc_info = mb.get_releases_by_discid(discid, includes=['artist-credits', 'recordings'])\n+        logging.debug(f\"discid: [{discid}]\")\n+        # Debugging, will dump the entire xml/json data from musicbrainz\n+        # logging.debug(f\"disc_info: {disc_info}\")\n+\n     except mb.WebServiceError as exc:\n         logging.error(f\"Cant reach MB or cd not found ? - ERROR: {exc}\")\n         u.database_updater(False, job)\n-        return \"\"\n-    try:\n-        # We never make it to here if the mb fails\n-        if 'disc' in infos:\n-            artist = release['artist-credit'][0]['artist']['name']\n-            no_of_titles = infos['disc']['offset-count']\n-        elif 'cdstub' in infos:\n-            artist = infos['cdstub']['artist']\n-            no_of_titles = infos['cdstub']['track-count']\n-            new_year = ''\n-\n-        logging.debug(f\"artist====={artist}\")\n-        if 'disc' in infos:\n-            logging.debug(f\"do have artwork?======{release['cover-art-archive']['artwork']}\")\n-        elif 'cdstub' in infos:\n-            logging.debug(\"do have artwork?======No (cdstub)\")\n-        # Get our front cover if it exists\n-        if get_cd_art(job, infos):\n-            logging.debug(\"we got an art image\")\n-        else:\n-            logging.debug(\"we didnt get art image\")\n-        # Set up the database properly for music cd's\n+        disc_info = \"\"\n+\n+    return disc_info\n+\n+\n+def check_musicbrainz_data(job, disc_info: dict) -> str:\n+    \"\"\"\n+    Process MusicBrainz metadata for a disc or CD stub and update the job database.\n+\n+    This function inspects the given `disc_info` dictionary for either full disc metadata\n+    or CD stub data. It extracts track information, album title, artist, release year,\n+    and number of tracks. It also attempts to download cover art if available, and\n+    updates the job's associated metadata in the database.\n+\n+    Parameters\n+    ----------\n+    job\n+        The job object that contains the current disc processing context, including\n+        logging and database update functionality.\n+    disc_info : dict\n+        A dictionary response from MusicBrainz containing metadata under either a\n+        'disc' or 'cdstub' key.\n+\n+    Returns\n+    -------\n+    str\n+        A combined artist and album title string if successful, or empty string\n+        if no valid data was processed.\n+\n+    Notes\n+    -----\n+    - If 'disc' metadata is present, the function checks for a CD-format release and processes the first one.\n+    - If only 'cdstub' metadata is available, it uses that limited data instead.\n+    - Track data is passed to `process_tracks()` to record each entry.\n+    - Album metadata is recorded using `u.database_updater()`.\n+    - Attempts to retrieve album artwork if full release data is present.\n+    - Returns a string containing the \"Artist Title\" if successful, otherwise False.\n+    \"\"\"\n+\n+    music_data = \"\"\n+\n+    # Check if valid disc or cdstub data present in data\n+    # If not, stop and return an empty string\n+    if 'disc' not in disc_info and 'cdstub' not in disc_info:\n+        logging.error(\"No release information reported by MusicBrainz\")\n+        return music_data\n+\n+    if 'disc' in disc_info:\n+        logging.info(\"Processing as a disc\")\n+        release_list = disc_info['disc'].get('release-list', [])\n+        logging.debug(f\"Number of releases: {len(release_list)}\")\n+\n+        # Check returned data has a release_list (album release info), otherwise return empty\n+        if len(release_list) > 0:\n+            # Loop through release data and find first that is a CD\n+            for i in range(len(release_list)):\n+                logging.debug(f\"Checking release: [{i}] if CD\")\n+                medium_list = release_list[i].get('medium-list', [])\n+                # Check that medium_list is valid (has data) and that we have returned a CD\n+                # possible values are \"12' Vinyl\" or \"CD\" from testing\n+                if medium_list and medium_list[0].get('format') == \"CD\":\n+                    logging.info(f\"Release [{i}] is a CD, tracking on...\")\n+                    logging.debug(\"-\" * 50)\n+                    process_tracks(job, medium_list[0].get('track-list'))\n+                    logging.debug(\"-\" * 50)\n+\n+                    # Update ARM with disc info\n+                    release = disc_info['disc']['release-list'][i]\n+                    new_year = check_date(release)\n+                    title = str(release.get('title', 'no title'))\n+                    artist = release['artist-credit'][0]['artist']['name']\n+                    no_of_titles = disc_info['disc']['offset-count']\n+                    artist_title = artist + \" \" + title\n+                    # Set out release id as the CRC_ID\n+                    args = {\n+                        'job_id': str(job.job_id),\n+                        'crc_id': release['id'],\n+                        'hasnicetitle': True,\n+                        'year': str(new_year),\n+                        'year_auto': str(new_year),\n+                        'title': artist_title,\n+                        'title_auto': artist_title,\n+                        'no_of_titles': no_of_titles\n+                    }\n+                    logging.info(f\"CD args: {args}\")\n+                    u.database_updater(args, job)\n+                    logging.debug(f\"musicbrain works -  New title is {title}  New Year is: {new_year}\")\n+\n+                    # Get album art work\n+                    logging.info(f\"do have artwork?======{release['cover-art-archive']['artwork']}\")\n+                    if get_cd_art(job, disc_info):\n+                        logging.debug(\"we got an art image\")\n+                    else:\n+                        logging.debug(\"we didnt get art image\")\n+                    music_data = artist_title\n+\n+    # Run if not a disc, but a cdstub (limited data)\n+    # No check on release is done here, assuming cdstub is limited to CDs\n+    elif 'cdstub' in disc_info:\n+        logging.info(\"Processing as a cdstub\")\n+        process_tracks(job, disc_info['cdstub']['track-list'], is_stub=True)\n+\n+        # Update ARM with disc info\n+        title = str(disc_info['cdstub']['title'])\n+        artist = disc_info['cdstub']['artist']\n+        no_of_titles = disc_info['cdstub']['track-count']\n+        new_year = ''\n         artist_title = artist + \" \" + title\n         args = {\n             'job_id': str(job.job_id),\n+            'crc_id': disc_info['cdstub']['id'],\n+            'hasnicetitle': True,\n             'year': new_year,\n             'year_auto': new_year,\n             'title': artist_title,\n             'title_auto': artist_title,\n             'no_of_titles': no_of_titles\n         }\n+        logging.info(f\"cdstub args: {args}\")\n         u.database_updater(args, job)\n-    except Exception as exc:\n-        artist_title = \"Not identified\" if not title else title\n-        logging.error(f\"Try 2 -  ERROR: {exc}\")\n-        u.database_updater(False, job)\n-    return artist_title\n+        logging.info(\"do have artwork?======No (cdstub)\")\n+        logging.debug(f\"musicbrain works, but stubbed -  New title is {artist_title}\")\n+\n+        music_data = artist_title\n \n+    return music_data\n \n-def check_date(release):\n+\n+def check_date(release: dict) -> str:\n     \"\"\"\n-    Check for valid date\n-    :param release:\n-    :return: correct year\n+    Extract and normalize the release year from a MusicBrainz release dictionary.\n+\n+    If a 'date' field exists, trims it to just the year.\n+    If the full date is in the format 'YYYY-MM-DD', only the year ('YYYY') is returned.\n+    If no date is available, returns an empty string.\n+\n+    Parameters\n+    ----------\n+    release : dict\n+        A MusicBrainz release dictionary, possibly containing a 'date' field.\n+\n+    Returns\n+    -------\n+    str\n+        The release year as a string, or an empty string if no date is present.\n     \"\"\"\n     # Clean up the date and the title\n     if 'date' in release:\n@@ -150,16 +269,33 @@ def check_date(release):\n     return new_year\n \n \n-def get_title(discid, job):\n+def get_title(discid: str, job) -> str:\n     \"\"\"\n-    Ask musicbrainz.org for the release of the disc\n-    only gets the title of the album and artist\n+    Query MusicBrainz for the album title and artist associated with a disc ID.\n+\n+    This function uses the MusicBrainz API to retrieve the release title and artist name\n+    for a given disc. If a valid result is found, it updates the job's database entry\n+    and returns a sanitized string in the format \"Artist-Title\". If no valid release is\n+    found, or an error occurs, it updates the database with a failure and returns\n+    \"not identified\".\n+\n+    Parameters\n+    ----------\n+    discid : str\n+        The disc ID obtained from the `discid` package.\n+    job\n+        The job object used for accessing the app version and updating the database.\n \n-    :param discid: identification object from discid package\n-    :param job: the job object for the database entry\n-    :return: the label of the disc as a string or \"\" if nothing was found\n+    Returns\n+    -------\n+    str\n+        The sanitized \"Artist-Title\" string if the disc is identified,\n+        or \"not identified\" if no match is found or an error occurs.\n \n-    Notes: dont try to use logging here - doing so will break the arm setup_logging() function\n+    Notes\n+    -----\n+    Avoid using logging in this function prior to the `setup_logging()` call,\n+    as it may interfere with ARM\u2019s logger initialization.\n     \"\"\"\n \n     # Tell musicbrainz what your app is, and how to contact you\n@@ -167,19 +303,19 @@ def get_title(discid, job):\n     # at http://wiki.musicbrainz.org/XML_Web_Service/Rate_Limiting )\n     mb.set_useragent(\"arm\", version=str(job.arm_version), contact=\"https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine\")\n     try:\n-        infos = mb.get_releases_by_discid(discid, includes=['artist-credits'])\n-        logging.debug(f\"Infos: {infos}\")\n+        disc_info = mb.get_releases_by_discid(discid, includes=['artist-credits'])\n+        logging.debug(f\"disc_info: {disc_info}\")\n         logging.debug(f\"discid = {discid}\")\n-        if 'disc' in infos:\n-            title = str(infos['disc']['release-list'][0]['title'])\n+        if 'disc' in disc_info:\n+            title = str(disc_info['disc']['release-list'][0]['title'])\n             # Start setting our db stuff\n-            artist = str(infos['disc']['release-list'][0]['artist-credit'][0]['artist']['name'])\n-            crc_id = str(infos['disc']['release-list'][0]['id'])\n-        elif 'cdstub' in infos:\n-            title = str(infos['cdstub']['title'])\n-            artist = str(infos['cdstub']['artist'])\n+            artist = str(disc_info['disc']['release-list'][0]['artist-credit'][0]['artist']['name'])\n+            crc_id = str(disc_info['disc']['release-list'][0]['id'])\n+        elif 'cdstub' in disc_info:\n+            title = str(disc_info['cdstub']['title'])\n+            artist = str(disc_info['cdstub']['artist'])\n             # Different id format, but what can you do?\n-            crc_id = str(infos['cdstub']['id'])\n+            crc_id = str(disc_info['cdstub']['id'])\n         else:\n             u.database_updater(False, job)\n             return \"not identified\"\n@@ -198,25 +334,54 @@ def get_title(discid, job):\n         return \"not identified\"\n \n \n-def get_cd_art(job, infos):\n+def get_cd_art(job, disc_info: str) -> bool:\n     \"\"\"\n-    Ask musicbrainz.org for the art of the disc\n+    Retrieve and store CD artwork from MusicBrainz if available.\n \n-    :param job: the job object for the database entry\n-    :param infos: object/json returned from musicbrainz.org api\n-    :return:     True if we find the cd art - False if we didnt find the art\n+    This function searches the MusicBrainz release list for the first release that\n+    contains cover art. It then queries the Cover Art Archive for available images,\n+    updates the job record with the image URLs, and returns a success flag.\n+\n+    Parameters\n+    ----------\n+    job\n+        The job object containing the database record to update.\n+    disc_info : dict\n+        JSON object returned by the MusicBrainz API containing disc and release metadata.\n+\n+    Returns\n+    -------\n+    bool\n+        True if artwork was found and saved, False if no artwork was found or an error occurred.\n+\n+    Notes\n+    -----\n+    The function handles common MusicBrainz errors such as:\n+    - 400: Invalid release ID (not a valid UUID)\n+    - 404: No release exists with the given MBID\n+    - 503: Rate limit exceeded or service unavailable\n+    These errors are logged, and the job record is updated to reflect the failure.\n     \"\"\"\n     try:\n         # Use the build-in images from coverartarchive if available\n-        if 'disc' in infos:\n-            release_list = infos['disc']['release-list']\n+        if 'disc' in disc_info:\n+            release_list = disc_info['disc']['release-list']\n+            logging.debug(f\"release_list: {release_list}\")\n             first_release_with_artwork = next(\n                 (release for release in release_list if release.get('cover-art-archive', {}).get('artwork') != \"false\"),\n                 None\n             )\n+            logging.debug(f\"first_release_with_artwork: {first_release_with_artwork}\")\n \n             if first_release_with_artwork is not None:\n+                # Call function from\n+                #  https://python-musicbrainzngs.readthedocs.io/en/v0.7/api/#musicbrainzngs.get_image_list\n+                # 400: Releaseid is not a valid UUID\n+                # 404: No release exists with an MBID of releaseid\n+                # 503: Ratelimit exceeded\n                 artlist = mb.get_image_list(first_release_with_artwork['id'])\n+                logging.debug(f\"artlist: {artlist}\")\n+\n                 for image in artlist[\"images\"]:\n                     # We dont care if its verified ?\n                     if \"image\" in image:\n@@ -225,6 +390,7 @@ def get_cd_art(job, infos):\n                             'poster_url_auto': str(image[\"image\"])\n                         }\n                         u.database_updater(args, job)\n+                        logging.debug(f\"poster_url: {args['poster_url']} poster_url_auto: {args['poster_url_auto']}\")\n                         return True\n         return False\n     except mb.WebServiceError as exc:\n@@ -233,13 +399,32 @@ def get_cd_art(job, infos):\n         return False\n \n \n-def process_tracks(job, mb_track_list, is_stub=False):\n+def process_tracks(job, mb_track_list: dict, is_stub=False):\n     \"\"\"\n+    Process a list of MusicBrainz tracks and store them in the database.\n+\n+    Iterates over a list of track dictionaries obtained from MusicBrainz and\n+    extracts track number, length, and title. These are then stored using\n+    the `put_track` utility function. Handles both stub and full metadata modes.\n+\n+    Parameters\n+    ----------\n+    job\n+        The job object that contains metadata and database context.\n+    mb_track_list : list of dict\n+        List of track entries from MusicBrainz, either full recordings or stub data.\n+    is_stub : bool, optional\n+        If True, process tracks using stub (simplified) structure. Default is False.\n+\n+    Returns\n+    -------\n+    None\n \n-    :param job:\n-    :param mb_track_list:\n-    :param is_stub:\n-    :return:\n+    Notes\n+    -----\n+    - Tracks with missing or invalid lengths will be logged but still processed.\n+    - A default title like \"Untitled track X\" will be used if no title is found in stub mode.\n+    - Each processed track is stored using `u.put_track()`.\n     \"\"\"\n     for (idx, track) in enumerate(mb_track_list):\n         track_leng = 0\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "\ud83d\udc1b Fatal Error: Invalid literal for int() with base 10: 'A1'\n### Is there an existing issue for this?\n\n- [x] I have searched the existing issues\n\n### I have checked the wiki\n\n- [x] I have searched the wiki for this problem\n\n### Does this issue exist in the latest version?\n\n- [x] I'm using the latest release\n\n### Describe the bug?\n\nI am trying to rip an album (Linkin Park - Meteora 20th Anniversary) and 2 of the 3 discs fail with the same error. The primary audio disc succeeds, but the \"LPU Rarities 2.0\" and \"Live Rarities 2003-2004\" discs fail. I originally had this issue on ARM 2.10.3, and upgraded to 2.10.5, but that did not resolve the issue. Attached are the logs from attempting to rip the \"LPU Rarities 2.0\" disc. Debug logging is enabled. \n\nNote: when using \"freecddb\" for the GET_AUDIO_TITLE parameter in arm.yaml, the two failing cds were able to rip successfully. This is only an issue with using the \"musicbrainz\" option.\n\n### To Reproduce\n\n1. ARM 2.10.5 using musicbrainz for GET_AUDIO_TITLE parameter in arm.yaml\n2. Rip one of the discs used above (or possibly others, though I do not currently have other examples)\n\n### What OS are you seeing the problem on?\n\nall\n\n### ARM Release Version or Git hash (You can find this in the arm settings page)\n\nPython Version: 3.10.12\nARM Version: 2.10.5\nCurrent git version: 3f4cd7c\nDocker image id: 5ba8e857719b\n\n### Expected behavior?\n\nIt should rip fine without any issues\n\n### Relevant log output\n\n```shell\n[02-28-2025 14:57:50] DEBUG ARM: music_brainz.music_brainz discid = fmAlyTnA0j.qTjeAVVnJN_2XNuQ-\n[02-28-2025 14:57:50] ERROR ARM: main.<module> invalid literal for int() with base 10: 'A1'\nTraceback (most recent call last):\n  File \"/opt/arm/arm/ripper/main.py\", line 223, in <module>\n    main(log_file, job, args.protection)\n  File \"/opt/arm/arm/ripper/main.py\", line 116, in main\n    music_brainz.main(job)\n  File \"/opt/arm/arm/ripper/music_brainz.py\", line 25, in main\n    return music_brainz(discid, disc)\n  File \"/opt/arm/arm/ripper/music_brainz.py\", line 52, in music_brainz\n    process_tracks(job, infos['disc']['release-list'][0]['medium-list'][0]['track-list'])\n  File \"/opt/arm/arm/ripper/music_brainz.py\", line 250, in process_tracks\n    u.put_track(job, trackno, track_leng, \"n/a\", 0.1, False, \"ABCDE\", title)\n  File \"/opt/arm/arm/ripper/utils.py\", line 523, in put_track\n    f\"Track #{int(t_no):02} Length: {seconds: >4} fps: {float(fps):2.3f} \"\nValueError: invalid literal for int() with base 10: 'A1'\n[02-28-2025 14:57:50] ERROR ARM: main.<module> A fatal error has occurred and ARM is exiting.  See traceback below for details.\n```\n\n### Anything else?\n\n[Linkin-Park-Meteora-(20th-anniversary-edition)_174075460727.log](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/19029443/Linkin-Park-Meteora-.20th-anniversary-edition._174075460727.log)\n\n### Code of Conduct\n\n- [x] I agree to follow this project's Code of Conduct\n", "hints_text": "If youre having issues, please remember to read the [wiki](https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/wiki/FAQ) and follow the instructions carefully\nFrom the log, the musicbrainz database is returning track information for release on vinyl.\n\n'format': '12\" Vinyl'\n\nThe tracks showing as A1, A2,... and then B1, B2, ...\nrepresents them being side A/B of the LP.\n\nSince the \"position\" field looks to be just a number for each track starting at 1 to the end, maybe you would have to tweak a setting to ask the ripper to use it instead of the \"track\" field.\n@drr159 I have modified the code with a quick check to ensure that this error doesn't happen again\n\nThanks for adding your job log, made it much easier to see the cause of the issue.\n\nIf you checkout PR #1320 test with the CD again and post the results (with debug enabled), we can confirm the issue is resolved\n> @slycordinator  \n> Since the \"position\" field looks to be just a number for each track starting at 1 to the end, maybe you would have to tweak a setting to ask the ripper to use it instead of the \"track\" field.\n\nI explained it in more detail in the PR but in case you're not monitoring that: That's not a good idea, as it will lead to wrong metadata.\n\n---\n\n> @drr159 \n> The primary audio disc succeeds\n\nThis is likely just because it has the same discid as the regular release and musicbrainz happens to return those first.\nIf you look at the tags, my guess is it's not showing anything about anniversary in there.\n\n", "all_hints_text": "If youre having issues, please remember to read the [wiki](https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/wiki/FAQ) and follow the instructions carefully\nFrom the log, the musicbrainz database is returning track information for release on vinyl.\n\n'format': '12\" Vinyl'\n\nThe tracks showing as A1, A2,... and then B1, B2, ...\nrepresents them being side A/B of the LP.\n\nSince the \"position\" field looks to be just a number for each track starting at 1 to the end, maybe you would have to tweak a setting to ask the ripper to use it instead of the \"track\" field.\n@drr159 I have modified the code with a quick check to ensure that this error doesn't happen again\n\nThanks for adding your job log, made it much easier to see the cause of the issue.\n\nIf you checkout PR #1320 test with the CD again and post the results (with debug enabled), we can confirm the issue is resolved\n> @slycordinator  \n> Since the \"position\" field looks to be just a number for each track starting at 1 to the end, maybe you would have to tweak a setting to ask the ripper to use it instead of the \"track\" field.\n\nI explained it in more detail in the PR but in case you're not monitoring that: That's not a good idea, as it will lead to wrong metadata.\n\n---\n\n> @drr159 \n> The primary audio disc succeeds\n\nThis is likely just because it has the same discid as the regular release and musicbrainz happens to return those first.\nIf you look at the tags, my guess is it's not showing anything about anniversary in there.\nI have this error as well, specifically with this release: https://musicbrainz.org/release/b5d64866-f896-426f-b239-31756c99c6d1 - this is a box set release with 2xLP and 1 CD, as I\u2019m trying to rip the CD it seems musicbrainz delivers the first entry to ARM and therefore gets \u2018A1\u2019 as incorrect title number. Is there a workaround I could apply? It is the correct release in Musicbrainz as there is only one and I checked it against the original.\n\nEdit: I tried uploading the log file, but for some reason it does not show up. Exert from the file:\n```\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: ******************* End of config parameters *******************\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: Checking for fstab entry.\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: fstab entry is: /dev/sr0  /mnt/dev/sr0  udf,iso9660  users,noauto,exec,utf8,ro  0  0\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:artist>, uncaught attribute type-id\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:artist>, uncaught attribute type-id\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:recording>, uncaught <first-release-date>\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:artist>, uncaught attribute type-id\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:recording>, uncaught <first-release-date>\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:artist>, uncaught attribute type-id\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:recording>, uncaught <first-release-date>\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:artist>, uncaught attribute type-id\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:recording>, uncaught <first-release-date>\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:artist>, uncaught attribute type-id\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:recording>, uncaught <first-release-date>\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:artist>, uncaught attribute type-id\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:recording>, uncaught <first-release-date>\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:artist>, uncaught attribute type-id\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:recording>, uncaught <first-release-date>\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:artist>, uncaught attribute type-id\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:recording>, uncaught <first-release-date>\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:artist>, uncaught attribute type-id\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:recording>, uncaught <first-release-date>\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:artist>, uncaught attribute type-id\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:recording>, uncaught <first-release-date>\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:artist>, uncaught attribute type-id\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:recording>, uncaught <first-release-date>\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:artist>, uncaught attribute type-id\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:recording>, uncaught <first-release-date>\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:artist>, uncaught attribute type-id\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:recording>, uncaught <first-release-date>\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:artist>, uncaught attribute type-id\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:recording>, uncaught <first-release-date>\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:artist>, uncaught attribute type-id\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:recording>, uncaught <first-release-date>\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:artist>, uncaught attribute type-id\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:recording>, uncaught <first-release-date>\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:artist>, uncaught attribute type-id\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:recording>, uncaught <first-release-date>\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:artist>, uncaught attribute type-id\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:recording>, uncaught <first-release-date>\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:artist>, uncaught attribute type-id\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:recording>, uncaught <first-release-date>\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:artist>, uncaught attribute type-id\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] INFO ARM: in <ws2:recording>, uncaught <first-release-date>\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] ERROR ARM: invalid literal for int() with base 10: \u2018A1\u2019\nTraceback (most recent call last):\n  File \"/opt/arm/arm/ripper/main.py\", line 225, in <module>\n    main(log_file, job, args.protection)\n  File \"/opt/arm/arm/ripper/main.py\", line 116, in main\n    music_brainz.main(job)\n  File \"/opt/arm/arm/ripper/music_brainz.py\", line 25, in main\n    return music_brainz(discid, disc)\n  File \"/opt/arm/arm/ripper/music_brainz.py\", line 56, in music_brainz\n    process_tracks(job, infos['disc']['release-list'][0]['medium-list'][0]['track-list\u2019])\n  File \"/opt/arm/arm/ripper/music_brainz.py\", line 258, in process_tracks\n    u.put_track(job, trackno, track_leng, \"n/a\", 0.1, False, \"ABCDE\", title)\n  File \"/opt/arm/arm/ripper/utils.py\", line 508, in put_track\n    f\"Track #{int(t_no):02} Length: {seconds: >4} fps: {float(fps):2.3f} \u201c\nValueError: invalid literal for int() with base 10: \u2018A1\u2019\n[09-14-2025 19:22:24] ERROR ARM: A fatal error has occurred and ARM is exiting.  See traceback below for details.\n[09-14-2025 19:22:27] INFO ARM: Releasing current job from drive\n```\n\n\n<!-- Uploading \"Winterka\u0308lte.log\"... \u2014>\nIf you know how to apply PR patches you can try the PR linked above your post.\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/commit/b11387519248267e496c86d7f6cde3346d918613", "https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/commit/cd033503f7ec8bf5320b8bd2a4fcffac09ade199", "https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/commit/ea3db8b23ec1ff7fbd6c1cb6faf2baa6cae457c0", "https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/commit/57c4558b900ac759077b9189410e0b489cebb2bf", "https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/commit/de6b7f2c8a1a474ddc39bdbebb17a764a1d5af39", "https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/commit/1bb3536411bb98bc54e412131d23656494c85a8d", "https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/commit/721856095dc01af6633a9d9e87786a3f77e385c6", "https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/commit/9c5a8660449b05e890edbf5ea10f5da4752e06e7", "https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/commit/d4667996a65d830d97cd4ea788d9f88645e679b5"], "created_at": "2025-07-09T13:23:45Z"}
{"repo": "automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine", "pull_number": 1472, "instance_id": "automatic-ripping-machine__automatic-ripping-machine-1472", "issue_numbers": [1353], "base_commit": "65391f6dbb2aa316de95a39a62461bef06a00217", "patch": "diff --git a/arm_wiki/Status-Known-Issues.md b/arm_wiki/Status-Known-Issues.md\nindex 770e13efb..3ab841173 100644\n--- a/arm_wiki/Status-Known-Issues.md\n+++ b/arm_wiki/Status-Known-Issues.md\n@@ -1,7 +1,26 @@\n # Known Issues\n \n-The following is a list of known issues relating to ARM:\n+The folllowing is a list of known issues that can cause issues during use of ARM, with potential work arounds.\n \n-* If the host running the container mid-job, any data that wasn't at rest is lost. Additionally, the job logic will be lest in a broken state and must be deleted.\n-* Movies with a `/` in the name can break the rip\n-* SQLite has a read / write limit, depending on ARM use the database can enter a state where ripping fails due to an inability to read or write data to the database. (resolved in 3.x)\n\\ No newline at end of file\n+## Ripping\n+\n+* **Issue:** If the host running the container mid-job, any data that wasn't at rest is lost. Additionally, the job logic will be lest in a broken state and must be deleted.\n+**Solution:** abandon the old job and start a new rip.\n+\n+* **Issue:** Movies with a `/` in the name can break the rip.\n+**Solution:** none at present\n+\n+* **Issue:** SQLite has a read / write limit, depending on ARM use the database can enter a state where ripping fails due to an inability to read or write data to the database. \n+**Solution:** planned for resolution in 3.x [Development Path](Status-Roadmap)\n+\n+* **Issue:** Ubuntu kernel 5.15.134 is known to break ARM per #1353\n+**Solution:** Upgrade host Ubuntu system to a later kernel\n+\n+```bash\n+Mar 25 16:55:30 ripperbox kernel: UDF-fs: error (device sr5): udf_fiiter_advance_blk: extent after position 2016 not allocated in directory (ino 269)\n+Mar 25 16:55:30 ripperbox kernel: UDF-fs: error (device sr5): udf_verify_fi: directory (ino 269) has entry where CRC length (36) does not match entry length (240)\n+```\n+\n+## User Iterface\n+\n+* Running in dark mode can cause some of the text and boxes to not display correctly\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "UDF-fs: Error??\n### Is there an existing issue for this?\n\n- [x] I have searched the existing issues\n\n### Does this issue exist in the latest version?\n\n- [x] I'm using the latest release\n\n### Describe the bug?\n\nDisc loads into Ripper UI  (it recognized a disc has been inserted) - but no processing happens  - it just stops. Manually searching for a title works and can be updated, but no ripping takes place.. system logs show file issue.. \nI do have a purchased MKV perma key and it has been working flawlessly.. I just ripped over 50 discs, and added Hard Days Night disk and everything stopped working.. multiple reboots, multiple restarts, multiple updates - no success.. on any of my 7 drives..  \nNo configuration parameters have been changed, no hardware has been added or removed.\n\n\n\n### To Reproduce\n\nUsing Portainer 2.21.12 on top of Docker - Ubuntu 22.04.5 - no issues to date. all packages and security patches are up to date.\n\n\n### Built from source files ?\n\n- [ ] I Built the image from source\n\n### What architecture are you seeing the problem on?\n\namd64\n\n### Expected behavior?\n\nInsert disk, starts the decryption  / ripping process. \n\n### Relevant log output\n\n```shell\nMar 25 16:55:30 ripperbox kernel: UDF-fs: error (device sr5): udf_fiiter_advance_blk: extent after position 2016 not allocated in directory (ino 269)\nMar 25 16:55:30 ripperbox kernel: UDF-fs: error (device sr5): udf_verify_fi: directory (ino 269) has entry where CRC length (36) does not match entry length (240)\n```\n\n### Anything else?\n\n_No response_\n\n### Code of Conduct\n\n- [x] I agree to follow this project's Code of Conduct\n", "hints_text": "If youre having issues, please remember to read the [wiki](https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/wiki/FAQ) and follow the instructions carefully\nThat's an odd issue\n\nI presume this is a data disk that you are trying to backup or copy?\nARM should have no issues reading them.\n\ncan you confirm\n1. Did anything change from a previous rip to now?\n2. Where in the process is this error occurring?\n3. If you try a disc that previously worked, does that throw the same error\nAfter Hours of research, the only thing that changed was the applying\r\nupdates to my Ubuntu 22.04 - jammy - Apparently, kernel 5.15.134 broke the\r\nability to read a dvd file system..\r\n\r\n it just so happened that I updated the container at the same time I\r\napplied my updates and it wouldnt read any dvds in any of my 7 drives after\r\nripping over 50 the day before.\r\n\r\nI couldn\u2019t get it rolled back so I updated to 24.04 and it\u2019s working again.\r\nDefinitely a word of warning for Jammy users and Kernel 5.15.134!\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nOn Fri, Apr 4, 2025 at 5:00\u202fPM Mtech ***@***.***> wrote:\r\n\r\n> That's an odd issue\r\n>\r\n> I presume this is a data disk that you are trying to backup or copy?\r\n> ARM should have no issues reading them.\r\n>\r\n> can you confirm\r\n>\r\n>    1. Did anything change from a previous rip to now?\r\n>    2. Where in the process is this error occurring?\r\n>    3. If you try a disc that previously worked, does that throw the same\r\n>    error\r\n>\r\n> \u2014\r\n> Reply to this email directly, view it on GitHub\r\n> <https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/issues/1353#issuecomment-2779721812>,\r\n> or unsubscribe\r\n> <https://github.com/notifications/unsubscribe-auth/A6CVELYPS3QKKEOURH6VECL2X36HZAVCNFSM6AAAAABZYVS6ZKVHI2DSMVQWIX3LMV43OSLTON2WKQ3PNVWWK3TUHMZDONZZG4ZDCOBRGI>\r\n> .\r\n> You are receiving this because you authored the thread.Message ID:\r\n> <automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/issues/1353/2779721812\r\n> @github.com>\r\n> [image: microtechno9000]*microtechno9000* left a comment\r\n> (automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine#1353)\r\n> <https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/issues/1353#issuecomment-2779721812>\r\n>\r\n> That's an odd issue\r\n>\r\n> I presume this is a data disk that you are trying to backup or copy?\r\n> ARM should have no issues reading them.\r\n>\r\n> can you confirm\r\n>\r\n>    1. Did anything change from a previous rip to now?\r\n>    2. Where in the process is this error occurring?\r\n>    3. If you try a disc that previously worked, does that throw the same\r\n>    error\r\n>\r\n> \u2014\r\n> Reply to this email directly, view it on GitHub\r\n> <https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/issues/1353#issuecomment-2779721812>,\r\n> or unsubscribe\r\n> <https://github.com/notifications/unsubscribe-auth/A6CVELYPS3QKKEOURH6VECL2X36HZAVCNFSM6AAAAABZYVS6ZKVHI2DSMVQWIX3LMV43OSLTON2WKQ3PNVWWK3TUHMZDONZZG4ZDCOBRGI>\r\n> .\r\n> You are receiving this because you authored the thread.Message ID:\r\n> <automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/issues/1353/2779721812\r\n> @github.com>\r\n>\r\n\nCould you raise a PR and add to [known issue](https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/blob/892a5f120929ffefbf6409ed851be1c9ac0c8559/arm_wiki/Status-Known-Issues.md)\nCan confirm this issue as well. I was working through this on another project and decided to test ARM and it was broken too.  I tried kernel 5.15.134 and 5.15.136 with issues on both. \n\nI changed my 22.04 instance over to the 6.8 kernel (6.8.0-57) and the issue is resolved. \n\nFYI There's a patch forthcoming for the 5.15 kernel as well. \nhttps://bugs.launchpad.net/ubuntu/+source/linux/+bug/2103598\n\nOutside of maybe documenting this known issue, I don't think this should be a bug in ARM, especially if canonical plans to resolve this on the next release cycle. \nNot a bug, a documentation update only to capture in the FAQ for users running Ubuntu kernel 5.15\nI added a line to the known issue file - let me know if I provided enough\r\ninfo - apologies been out of town.\r\n\r\nOn Fri, Apr 4, 2025 at 9:14\u202fPM Mtech ***@***.***> wrote:\r\n\r\n> Could you raise a PR and add to (known\r\n> issue)[arm_wiki/Status-Known-Issues.md]\r\n>\r\n> \u2014\r\n> Reply to this email directly, view it on GitHub\r\n> <https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/issues/1353#issuecomment-2780089066>,\r\n> or unsubscribe\r\n> <https://github.com/notifications/unsubscribe-auth/A6CVEL4MLAU42O3TDMFIZJT2X44AVAVCNFSM6AAAAABZYVS6ZKVHI2DSMVQWIX3LMV43OSLTON2WKQ3PNVWWK3TUHMZDOOBQGA4DSMBWGY>\r\n> .\r\n> You are receiving this because you authored the thread.Message ID:\r\n> <automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/issues/1353/2780089066\r\n> @github.com>\r\n> [image: microtechno9000]*microtechno9000* left a comment\r\n> (automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine#1353)\r\n> <https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/issues/1353#issuecomment-2780089066>\r\n>\r\n> Could you raise a PR and add to (known\r\n> issue)[arm_wiki/Status-Known-Issues.md]\r\n>\r\n> \u2014\r\n> Reply to this email directly, view it on GitHub\r\n> <https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/issues/1353#issuecomment-2780089066>,\r\n> or unsubscribe\r\n> <https://github.com/notifications/unsubscribe-auth/A6CVEL4MLAU42O3TDMFIZJT2X44AVAVCNFSM6AAAAABZYVS6ZKVHI2DSMVQWIX3LMV43OSLTON2WKQ3PNVWWK3TUHMZDOOBQGA4DSMBWGY>\r\n> .\r\n> You are receiving this because you authored the thread.Message ID:\r\n> <automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/issues/1353/2780089066\r\n> @github.com>\r\n>\r\n\nI dont see a pull request for the change \n\nDid you follow the [Wiki Guide](https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/wiki/Contribute-Wiki)?\n\n", "all_hints_text": "If youre having issues, please remember to read the [wiki](https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/wiki/FAQ) and follow the instructions carefully\nThat's an odd issue\n\nI presume this is a data disk that you are trying to backup or copy?\nARM should have no issues reading them.\n\ncan you confirm\n1. Did anything change from a previous rip to now?\n2. Where in the process is this error occurring?\n3. If you try a disc that previously worked, does that throw the same error\nAfter Hours of research, the only thing that changed was the applying\r\nupdates to my Ubuntu 22.04 - jammy - Apparently, kernel 5.15.134 broke the\r\nability to read a dvd file system..\r\n\r\n it just so happened that I updated the container at the same time I\r\napplied my updates and it wouldnt read any dvds in any of my 7 drives after\r\nripping over 50 the day before.\r\n\r\nI couldn\u2019t get it rolled back so I updated to 24.04 and it\u2019s working again.\r\nDefinitely a word of warning for Jammy users and Kernel 5.15.134!\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nOn Fri, Apr 4, 2025 at 5:00\u202fPM Mtech ***@***.***> wrote:\r\n\r\n> That's an odd issue\r\n>\r\n> I presume this is a data disk that you are trying to backup or copy?\r\n> ARM should have no issues reading them.\r\n>\r\n> can you confirm\r\n>\r\n>    1. Did anything change from a previous rip to now?\r\n>    2. Where in the process is this error occurring?\r\n>    3. If you try a disc that previously worked, does that throw the same\r\n>    error\r\n>\r\n> \u2014\r\n> Reply to this email directly, view it on GitHub\r\n> <https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/issues/1353#issuecomment-2779721812>,\r\n> or unsubscribe\r\n> <https://github.com/notifications/unsubscribe-auth/A6CVELYPS3QKKEOURH6VECL2X36HZAVCNFSM6AAAAABZYVS6ZKVHI2DSMVQWIX3LMV43OSLTON2WKQ3PNVWWK3TUHMZDONZZG4ZDCOBRGI>\r\n> .\r\n> You are receiving this because you authored the thread.Message ID:\r\n> <automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/issues/1353/2779721812\r\n> @github.com>\r\n> [image: microtechno9000]*microtechno9000* left a comment\r\n> (automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine#1353)\r\n> <https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/issues/1353#issuecomment-2779721812>\r\n>\r\n> That's an odd issue\r\n>\r\n> I presume this is a data disk that you are trying to backup or copy?\r\n> ARM should have no issues reading them.\r\n>\r\n> can you confirm\r\n>\r\n>    1. Did anything change from a previous rip to now?\r\n>    2. Where in the process is this error occurring?\r\n>    3. If you try a disc that previously worked, does that throw the same\r\n>    error\r\n>\r\n> \u2014\r\n> Reply to this email directly, view it on GitHub\r\n> <https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/issues/1353#issuecomment-2779721812>,\r\n> or unsubscribe\r\n> <https://github.com/notifications/unsubscribe-auth/A6CVELYPS3QKKEOURH6VECL2X36HZAVCNFSM6AAAAABZYVS6ZKVHI2DSMVQWIX3LMV43OSLTON2WKQ3PNVWWK3TUHMZDONZZG4ZDCOBRGI>\r\n> .\r\n> You are receiving this because you authored the thread.Message ID:\r\n> <automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/issues/1353/2779721812\r\n> @github.com>\r\n>\r\n\nCould you raise a PR and add to [known issue](https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/blob/892a5f120929ffefbf6409ed851be1c9ac0c8559/arm_wiki/Status-Known-Issues.md)\nCan confirm this issue as well. I was working through this on another project and decided to test ARM and it was broken too.  I tried kernel 5.15.134 and 5.15.136 with issues on both. \n\nI changed my 22.04 instance over to the 6.8 kernel (6.8.0-57) and the issue is resolved. \n\nFYI There's a patch forthcoming for the 5.15 kernel as well. \nhttps://bugs.launchpad.net/ubuntu/+source/linux/+bug/2103598\n\nOutside of maybe documenting this known issue, I don't think this should be a bug in ARM, especially if canonical plans to resolve this on the next release cycle. \nNot a bug, a documentation update only to capture in the FAQ for users running Ubuntu kernel 5.15\nI added a line to the known issue file - let me know if I provided enough\r\ninfo - apologies been out of town.\r\n\r\nOn Fri, Apr 4, 2025 at 9:14\u202fPM Mtech ***@***.***> wrote:\r\n\r\n> Could you raise a PR and add to (known\r\n> issue)[arm_wiki/Status-Known-Issues.md]\r\n>\r\n> \u2014\r\n> Reply to this email directly, view it on GitHub\r\n> <https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/issues/1353#issuecomment-2780089066>,\r\n> or unsubscribe\r\n> <https://github.com/notifications/unsubscribe-auth/A6CVEL4MLAU42O3TDMFIZJT2X44AVAVCNFSM6AAAAABZYVS6ZKVHI2DSMVQWIX3LMV43OSLTON2WKQ3PNVWWK3TUHMZDOOBQGA4DSMBWGY>\r\n> .\r\n> You are receiving this because you authored the thread.Message ID:\r\n> <automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/issues/1353/2780089066\r\n> @github.com>\r\n> [image: microtechno9000]*microtechno9000* left a comment\r\n> (automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine#1353)\r\n> <https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/issues/1353#issuecomment-2780089066>\r\n>\r\n> Could you raise a PR and add to (known\r\n> issue)[arm_wiki/Status-Known-Issues.md]\r\n>\r\n> \u2014\r\n> Reply to this email directly, view it on GitHub\r\n> <https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/issues/1353#issuecomment-2780089066>,\r\n> or unsubscribe\r\n> <https://github.com/notifications/unsubscribe-auth/A6CVEL4MLAU42O3TDMFIZJT2X44AVAVCNFSM6AAAAABZYVS6ZKVHI2DSMVQWIX3LMV43OSLTON2WKQ3PNVWWK3TUHMZDOOBQGA4DSMBWGY>\r\n> .\r\n> You are receiving this because you authored the thread.Message ID:\r\n> <automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/issues/1353/2780089066\r\n> @github.com>\r\n>\r\n\nI dont see a pull request for the change \n\nDid you follow the [Wiki Guide](https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/wiki/Contribute-Wiki)?\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/commit/d5f7c3a567c2db43f0b4893bcae112b3a06a4cbf"], "created_at": "2025-07-20T13:33:26Z"}
{"repo": "automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine", "pull_number": 1396, "instance_id": "automatic-ripping-machine__automatic-ripping-machine-1396", "issue_numbers": [1381], "base_commit": "8ae2fae4edd4b64c8f295d4c674b4bb3f2f3e7ed", "patch": "diff --git a/VERSION b/VERSION\nindex d91346fd9..07d875c2d 100755\n--- a/VERSION\n+++ b/VERSION\n@@ -1,1 +1,1 @@\n-2.15.1\n\\ No newline at end of file\n+2.15.2\ndiff --git a/arm/models/system_info.py b/arm/models/system_info.py\nindex 0c91f0931..5ebec149c 100644\n--- a/arm/models/system_info.py\n+++ b/arm/models/system_info.py\n@@ -2,6 +2,7 @@\n import psutil\n import re\n import subprocess\n+import logging\n \n from arm.ui import db\n \n@@ -27,37 +28,42 @@ def get_cpu_info(self):\n         function to collect and return some cpu info\n         ideally want to return {name} @ {speed} Ghz\n         \"\"\"\n-        self.cpu = \"Unknown\"\n+        self.cpu = \"Unable to Identify\"\n+        logging.debug(\"****** Getting CPU Info ******\")\n+\n         if platform.system() == \"Windows\":\n             self.cpu = platform.processor()\n         elif platform.system() == \"Darwin\":\n             self.cpu = subprocess.check_output(['/usr/sbin/sysctl', \"-n\", \"machdep.cpu.brand_string\"]).strip()\n         elif platform.system() == \"Linux\":\n             command = \"cat /proc/cpuinfo\"\n-            fulldump = str(subprocess.check_output(command, shell=True).strip())\n+            fulldump = subprocess.check_output(command, shell=True).decode()\n+            # logging.debug(f\"Full cpuinfo: {fulldump}\")\n+\n             # Take any float trailing \"MHz\", some whitespace, and a colon.\n-            speeds = re.search(r\"\\\\nmodel name\\\\t:.*?GHz\\\\n\", fulldump)\n-            if speeds:\n-                # We have intel CPU\n-                speeds = str(speeds.group())\n-                speeds = speeds.replace('\\\\n', ' ')\n-                speeds = speeds.replace('\\\\t', ' ')\n-                speeds = speeds.replace('model name :', '')\n-                self.cpu = speeds\n+            # like: model name  : Intel(R) Celeron(R) G4930T CPU @ 3.00GHz\n+            intel_match = re.search(r\"model name\\s*:\\s*(.*?GHz)\", fulldump)\n+            logging.debug(f\"Intel output: {intel_match}\")\n+            if intel_match:\n+                self.cpu = intel_match.group(1)\n+\n             # AMD CPU\n-            amd_name_full = re.search(r\"model name\\\\t: (.*?)\\\\n\", fulldump)\n+            amd_name_full = re.search(r\"model name\\s*:\\s*(.*)\", fulldump)\n+            logging.debug(f\"AMD output: {amd_name_full}\")\n             if amd_name_full:\n                 amd_name = amd_name_full.group(1)\n-                amd_mhz = re.search(r\"cpu MHz(?:\\\\t)*: ([.0-9]*)\\\\n\", fulldump)  # noqa: W605\n+                amd_mhz = re.search(r\"cpu MHz\\s*:\\s*([.0-9]+)\", fulldump)  # noqa: W605\n                 if amd_mhz:\n                     amd_ghz = round(float(amd_mhz.group(1)) / 1000, 2)  # this is a good idea\n                     self.cpu = str(amd_name) + \" @ \" + str(amd_ghz) + \" GHz\"\n+\n             # ARM64 CPU\n-            arm_cpu = re.search(r\"\\\\nmodel name\\\\t:(.*?)\\\\n\", fulldump)\n+            arm_cpu = re.search(r\"model name\\s*:\\s*(.*)n\", fulldump)\n+            logging.debug(f\"ARM64 output: {arm_cpu}\")\n             if arm_cpu:\n                 self.cpu = str(arm_cpu.group(1))[:19]\n-        else:\n-            self.cpu = \"N/A\"\n+\n+        logging.debug(\"****************************\")\n \n     def get_memory(self):\n         \"\"\" get the system total memory \"\"\"\ndiff --git a/arm/ui/settings/settings.py b/arm/ui/settings/settings.py\nindex afa6c91fb..8c80e610f 100644\n--- a/arm/ui/settings/settings.py\n+++ b/arm/ui/settings/settings.py\n@@ -407,10 +407,9 @@ def update_cpu():\n         current_system.name = new_system.name\n         current_system.cpu = new_system.cpu\n         db.session.add(current_system)\n-\n     else:\n-        app.logger.debug(f\"Name old [] new [{new_system.name}]\")\n-        app.logger.debug(f\"Name old [] new [{new_system.cpu}]\")\n+        app.logger.debug(f\"Name old [No Info] new [{new_system.name}]\")\n+        app.logger.debug(f\"Name old [No Info] new [{new_system.cpu}]\")\n         db.session.add(new_system)\n \n     app.logger.debug(\"****** End System Information ******\")\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "\ud83d\udc1b CPU update is incorrect\n### Is there an existing issue for this?\n\n- [x] I have searched the existing issues\n\n### I have checked the wiki\n\n- [x] I have searched the wiki for this problem\n\n### Does this issue exist in the latest version?\n\n- [x] I'm using the latest release\n\n### Describe the bug?\n\nSince adding the \"Update CPU info\" button, it has not correctly displayed the CPU name.\n\nI am running the docker release and the model name (from /proc/cpuinfo) is \n`Intel(R) Celeron(R) G4930T CPU @ 3.00GHz`\n\nIn settings I see\n`CPU: Intel(R) Celeron(R `\n\nSeems to not be escaping the parentheses in the name correctly\n\n### To Reproduce\n\nHave a CPU with multiple escapable characters in the name (I guess) and then try to update CPU info from the settings menu.\n\n### What OS are you seeing the problem on?\n\nOther (please state in Anything else? section)\n\n### ARM Release Version or Git hash (You can find this in the arm settings page)\n\nPython version: 3.10.12\nA.R.M version: 2.13.0\nCurrent git version: 1122d0e\n\n### Expected behavior?\n\nShould show full CPU name\n\n### Relevant log output\n\n```shell\n[2025-05-05 18:59:53,064] INFO ARM: settings.update_cpu Updated CPU Details with new info - ARM Server -  Intel(R) Celeron(R\n\nthat is the full output\n```\n\n### Anything else?\n\n_No response_\n\n### Code of Conduct\n\n- [x] I agree to follow this project's Code of Conduct\n", "hints_text": "If youre having issues, please remember to read the [wiki](https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/wiki/FAQ) and follow the instructions carefully\nDid it work in the previous update?\nNo, previously it displayed something like \"Intel Celeron Processor\" and that's all\n\n", "all_hints_text": "If youre having issues, please remember to read the [wiki](https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/wiki/FAQ) and follow the instructions carefully\nDid it work in the previous update?\nNo, previously it displayed something like \"Intel Celeron Processor\" and that's all\nHad a further look, Intel system info is being stripped.\nResolved the issue and will have a patch soon\n\n```bash\n[2025-05-25 16:58:10,274] DEBUG ARM: settings.update_cpu ****** System Information ******\n[2025-05-25 16:58:10,275] DEBUG ARM: settings.update_cpu Name old [ARM Server] new [ARM Server]\n[2025-05-25 16:58:10,275] DEBUG ARM: settings.update_cpu Name old [Unable to Identify] new [11th Gen Intel(R) Core(TM) i5-1135G7 @ 2.40GHz]\n[2025-05-25 16:58:10,275] DEBUG ARM: settings.update_cpu ****** End System Information ******\n```\nafter updating I am still seeing incorrect CPU info\n\nPython version: 3.10.12\nA.R.M version: 2.16.1\nCurrent git version: cdc7c1b\n\nafter clicking \"Update CPU\" I now see `Intel(R) Celero` so I'm actually seeing even less than I was before\n\n```\n[2025-07-01 09:32:40,114] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info ****** Getting CPU Info ******\n[2025-07-01 09:32:40,117] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info Intel output: <re.Match object; span=(67, 120), match='model name\\t: Intel(R) Celeron(R) G4930T CPU @ 3.>\n[2025-07-01 09:32:40,117] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info AMD output: <re.Match object; span=(67, 120), match='model name\\t: Intel(R) Celeron(R) G4930T CPU @ 3.>\n[2025-07-01 09:32:40,118] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info ARM64 output: <re.Match object; span=(67, 96), match='model name\\t: Intel(R) Celeron'>\n[2025-07-01 09:32:40,118] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info ****************************\n[2025-07-01 09:32:40,118] INFO ARM: settings.update_cpu Updated CPU Details with new info - ARM Server - Intel(R) Celero\n[2025-07-01 09:32:40,438] INFO ARM: settings.check_hw_transcode_support Intel QuickSync supported!\n[2025-07-01 09:32:40,439] INFO ARM: settings.check_hw_transcode_support Handbrake call successful\n[2025-07-01 09:33:20,530] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info ****** Getting CPU Info ******\n[2025-07-01 09:33:20,532] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info Intel output: <re.Match object; span=(67, 120), match='model name\\t: Intel(R) Celeron(R) G4930T CPU @ 3.>\n[2025-07-01 09:33:20,532] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info AMD output: <re.Match object; span=(67, 120), match='model name\\t: Intel(R) Celeron(R) G4930T CPU @ 3.>\n[2025-07-01 09:33:20,533] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info ARM64 output: <re.Match object; span=(67, 96), match='model name\\t: Intel(R) Celeron'>\n[2025-07-01 09:33:20,533] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info ****************************\n[2025-07-01 09:33:20,533] INFO ARM: settings.update_cpu Updated CPU Details with new info - ARM Server - Intel(R) Celero\n[2025-07-01 09:33:21,006] INFO ARM: settings.check_hw_transcode_support Intel QuickSync supported!\n[2025-07-01 09:33:21,006] INFO ARM: settings.check_hw_transcode_support Handbrake call successful\n```\non another machine with model \"Intel(R) Atom(TM) CPU D510   @ 1.66GHz\"\n```\n[2025-07-01 16:30:02,108] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info ****** Getting CPU Info ******\n[2025-07-01 16:30:02,120] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info Intel output: <re.Match object; span=(66, 117), match='model name\\t: Intel(R) Atom(TM) CPU D510   @ 1.66>\n[2025-07-01 16:30:02,122] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info AMD output: <re.Match object; span=(66, 117), match='model name\\t: Intel(R) Atom(TM) CPU D510   @ 1.66>\n[2025-07-01 16:30:02,124] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info ARM64 output: <re.Match object; span=(66, 81), match='model name\\t: In'>\n[2025-07-01 16:30:02,125] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info ****************************\n[2025-07-01 16:30:02,128] INFO ARM: settings.update_cpu Updated CPU Details with new info - ARM Server - I\n[2025-07-01 16:30:03,228] INFO ARM: settings.check_hw_transcode_support Intel QuickSync supported!\n[2025-07-01 16:30:03,229] INFO ARM: settings.check_hw_transcode_support Handbrake call successful\n```\nSeems the regex filters are failing, thanks for the logs, will check\nworking perfectly on my two systems\n\n```\n2025-07-20 13:21:10,860] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info ****** Getting CPU Info ******\n[2025-07-20 13:21:10,862] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info Regex output: <re.Match object; span=(67, 120), match='model name\\t: Intel(R) Celeron(R) G4930T CPU @ 3.>\n[2025-07-20 13:21:10,862] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info CPU Info: Intel(R) Celeron(R) G4930T CPU @ 3.00GHz\n[2025-07-20 13:21:10,862] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info ****************************\n```\n\n```\n[2025-07-20 13:24:01,320] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info ****** Getting CPU Info ******\n[2025-07-20 13:24:01,331] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info Regex output: <re.Match object; span=(66, 117), match='model name\\t: Intel(R) Atom(TM) CPU D510   @ 1.66>\n[2025-07-20 13:24:01,332] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info CPU Info: Intel(R) Atom(TM) CPU D510   @ 1.66GHz\n[2025-07-20 13:24:01,333] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info ****************************\n```\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/commit/6841dad38daa3c0bdf17234ef1bfebab1b4268ed", "https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/commit/4429e874ad796f381aff0a87126e17413d0ad39d", "https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/commit/adaa33945d5dc053674d44ed1f9a5be9b5b54bee", "https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/commit/95555536f40732faf59501c1df445256685c25e7", "https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/commit/12ed50c0778bdd635c0633c8dd1df2b5f9690887", "https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/commit/35b2d7c888a7f52a0c3c3015e7c534bc6ae0d74d"], "created_at": "2025-05-25T07:41:45Z"}
{"repo": "automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine", "pull_number": 1446, "instance_id": "automatic-ripping-machine__automatic-ripping-machine-1446", "issue_numbers": [1381], "base_commit": "203680945cc267dd56b102aac3fe95b9279aebdc", "patch": "diff --git a/VERSION b/VERSION\nindex 94dc0ec91..15d0fc4cf 100755\n--- a/VERSION\n+++ b/VERSION\n@@ -1,1 +1,1 @@\n-2.17.2\n+2.17.3\ndiff --git a/arm/models/system_info.py b/arm/models/system_info.py\nindex 5ebec149c..4fe5f88d3 100644\n--- a/arm/models/system_info.py\n+++ b/arm/models/system_info.py\n@@ -38,31 +38,17 @@ def get_cpu_info(self):\n         elif platform.system() == \"Linux\":\n             command = \"cat /proc/cpuinfo\"\n             fulldump = subprocess.check_output(command, shell=True).decode()\n-            # logging.debug(f\"Full cpuinfo: {fulldump}\")\n \n-            # Take any float trailing \"MHz\", some whitespace, and a colon.\n-            # like: model name  : Intel(R) Celeron(R) G4930T CPU @ 3.00GHz\n-            intel_match = re.search(r\"model name\\s*:\\s*(.*?GHz)\", fulldump)\n-            logging.debug(f\"Intel output: {intel_match}\")\n-            if intel_match:\n-                self.cpu = intel_match.group(1)\n-\n-            # AMD CPU\n-            amd_name_full = re.search(r\"model name\\s*:\\s*(.*)\", fulldump)\n-            logging.debug(f\"AMD output: {amd_name_full}\")\n-            if amd_name_full:\n-                amd_name = amd_name_full.group(1)\n-                amd_mhz = re.search(r\"cpu MHz\\s*:\\s*([.0-9]+)\", fulldump)  # noqa: W605\n-                if amd_mhz:\n-                    amd_ghz = round(float(amd_mhz.group(1)) / 1000, 2)  # this is a good idea\n-                    self.cpu = str(amd_name) + \" @ \" + str(amd_ghz) + \" GHz\"\n-\n-            # ARM64 CPU\n-            arm_cpu = re.search(r\"model name\\s*:\\s*(.*)n\", fulldump)\n-            logging.debug(f\"ARM64 output: {arm_cpu}\")\n-            if arm_cpu:\n-                self.cpu = str(arm_cpu.group(1))[:19]\n+            # Find the CPU Model Name\n+            # Intel     model name  : Intel(R) Celeron(R) G4930T CPU @ 3.00GHz\n+            # amd       model name  : AMD Ryzen 5 3600 6-Core Processor\n+            # arm       model name  : ARMv8 Processor rev 3 (v8l)\n+            regex_match = re.search(r\"model name\\s*:\\s*(.*)\", fulldump)\n+            logging.debug(f\"Regex output: {regex_match}\")\n+            if regex_match:\n+                self.cpu = regex_match.group(1)\n \n+        logging.debug(f\"CPU Info: {self.cpu}\")\n         logging.debug(\"****************************\")\n \n     def get_memory(self):\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "\ud83d\udc1b CPU update is incorrect\n### Is there an existing issue for this?\n\n- [x] I have searched the existing issues\n\n### I have checked the wiki\n\n- [x] I have searched the wiki for this problem\n\n### Does this issue exist in the latest version?\n\n- [x] I'm using the latest release\n\n### Describe the bug?\n\nSince adding the \"Update CPU info\" button, it has not correctly displayed the CPU name.\n\nI am running the docker release and the model name (from /proc/cpuinfo) is \n`Intel(R) Celeron(R) G4930T CPU @ 3.00GHz`\n\nIn settings I see\n`CPU: Intel(R) Celeron(R `\n\nSeems to not be escaping the parentheses in the name correctly\n\n### To Reproduce\n\nHave a CPU with multiple escapable characters in the name (I guess) and then try to update CPU info from the settings menu.\n\n### What OS are you seeing the problem on?\n\nOther (please state in Anything else? section)\n\n### ARM Release Version or Git hash (You can find this in the arm settings page)\n\nPython version: 3.10.12\nA.R.M version: 2.13.0\nCurrent git version: 1122d0e\n\n### Expected behavior?\n\nShould show full CPU name\n\n### Relevant log output\n\n```shell\n[2025-05-05 18:59:53,064] INFO ARM: settings.update_cpu Updated CPU Details with new info - ARM Server -  Intel(R) Celeron(R\n\nthat is the full output\n```\n\n### Anything else?\n\n_No response_\n\n### Code of Conduct\n\n- [x] I agree to follow this project's Code of Conduct\n", "hints_text": "If youre having issues, please remember to read the [wiki](https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/wiki/FAQ) and follow the instructions carefully\nDid it work in the previous update?\nNo, previously it displayed something like \"Intel Celeron Processor\" and that's all\nHad a further look, Intel system info is being stripped.\nResolved the issue and will have a patch soon\n\n```bash\n[2025-05-25 16:58:10,274] DEBUG ARM: settings.update_cpu ****** System Information ******\n[2025-05-25 16:58:10,275] DEBUG ARM: settings.update_cpu Name old [ARM Server] new [ARM Server]\n[2025-05-25 16:58:10,275] DEBUG ARM: settings.update_cpu Name old [Unable to Identify] new [11th Gen Intel(R) Core(TM) i5-1135G7 @ 2.40GHz]\n[2025-05-25 16:58:10,275] DEBUG ARM: settings.update_cpu ****** End System Information ******\n```\nafter updating I am still seeing incorrect CPU info\n\nPython version: 3.10.12\nA.R.M version: 2.16.1\nCurrent git version: cdc7c1b\n\nafter clicking \"Update CPU\" I now see `Intel(R) Celero` so I'm actually seeing even less than I was before\n\n```\n[2025-07-01 09:32:40,114] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info ****** Getting CPU Info ******\n[2025-07-01 09:32:40,117] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info Intel output: <re.Match object; span=(67, 120), match='model name\\t: Intel(R) Celeron(R) G4930T CPU @ 3.>\n[2025-07-01 09:32:40,117] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info AMD output: <re.Match object; span=(67, 120), match='model name\\t: Intel(R) Celeron(R) G4930T CPU @ 3.>\n[2025-07-01 09:32:40,118] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info ARM64 output: <re.Match object; span=(67, 96), match='model name\\t: Intel(R) Celeron'>\n[2025-07-01 09:32:40,118] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info ****************************\n[2025-07-01 09:32:40,118] INFO ARM: settings.update_cpu Updated CPU Details with new info - ARM Server - Intel(R) Celero\n[2025-07-01 09:32:40,438] INFO ARM: settings.check_hw_transcode_support Intel QuickSync supported!\n[2025-07-01 09:32:40,439] INFO ARM: settings.check_hw_transcode_support Handbrake call successful\n[2025-07-01 09:33:20,530] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info ****** Getting CPU Info ******\n[2025-07-01 09:33:20,532] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info Intel output: <re.Match object; span=(67, 120), match='model name\\t: Intel(R) Celeron(R) G4930T CPU @ 3.>\n[2025-07-01 09:33:20,532] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info AMD output: <re.Match object; span=(67, 120), match='model name\\t: Intel(R) Celeron(R) G4930T CPU @ 3.>\n[2025-07-01 09:33:20,533] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info ARM64 output: <re.Match object; span=(67, 96), match='model name\\t: Intel(R) Celeron'>\n[2025-07-01 09:33:20,533] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info ****************************\n[2025-07-01 09:33:20,533] INFO ARM: settings.update_cpu Updated CPU Details with new info - ARM Server - Intel(R) Celero\n[2025-07-01 09:33:21,006] INFO ARM: settings.check_hw_transcode_support Intel QuickSync supported!\n[2025-07-01 09:33:21,006] INFO ARM: settings.check_hw_transcode_support Handbrake call successful\n```\non another machine with model \"Intel(R) Atom(TM) CPU D510   @ 1.66GHz\"\n```\n[2025-07-01 16:30:02,108] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info ****** Getting CPU Info ******\n[2025-07-01 16:30:02,120] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info Intel output: <re.Match object; span=(66, 117), match='model name\\t: Intel(R) Atom(TM) CPU D510   @ 1.66>\n[2025-07-01 16:30:02,122] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info AMD output: <re.Match object; span=(66, 117), match='model name\\t: Intel(R) Atom(TM) CPU D510   @ 1.66>\n[2025-07-01 16:30:02,124] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info ARM64 output: <re.Match object; span=(66, 81), match='model name\\t: In'>\n[2025-07-01 16:30:02,125] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info ****************************\n[2025-07-01 16:30:02,128] INFO ARM: settings.update_cpu Updated CPU Details with new info - ARM Server - I\n[2025-07-01 16:30:03,228] INFO ARM: settings.check_hw_transcode_support Intel QuickSync supported!\n[2025-07-01 16:30:03,229] INFO ARM: settings.check_hw_transcode_support Handbrake call successful\n```\nSeems the regex filters are failing, thanks for the logs, will check\n\n", "all_hints_text": "If youre having issues, please remember to read the [wiki](https://github.com/automatic-ripping-machine/automatic-ripping-machine/wiki/FAQ) and follow the instructions carefully\nDid it work in the previous update?\nNo, previously it displayed something like \"Intel Celeron Processor\" and that's all\nHad a further look, Intel system info is being stripped.\nResolved the issue and will have a patch soon\n\n```bash\n[2025-05-25 16:58:10,274] DEBUG ARM: settings.update_cpu ****** System Information ******\n[2025-05-25 16:58:10,275] DEBUG ARM: settings.update_cpu Name old [ARM Server] new [ARM Server]\n[2025-05-25 16:58:10,275] DEBUG ARM: settings.update_cpu Name old [Unable to Identify] new [11th Gen Intel(R) Core(TM) i5-1135G7 @ 2.40GHz]\n[2025-05-25 16:58:10,275] DEBUG ARM: settings.update_cpu ****** End System Information ******\n```\nafter updating I am still seeing incorrect CPU info\n\nPython version: 3.10.12\nA.R.M version: 2.16.1\nCurrent git version: cdc7c1b\n\nafter clicking \"Update CPU\" I now see `Intel(R) Celero` so I'm actually seeing even less than I was before\n\n```\n[2025-07-01 09:32:40,114] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info ****** Getting CPU Info ******\n[2025-07-01 09:32:40,117] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info Intel output: <re.Match object; span=(67, 120), match='model name\\t: Intel(R) Celeron(R) G4930T CPU @ 3.>\n[2025-07-01 09:32:40,117] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info AMD output: <re.Match object; span=(67, 120), match='model name\\t: Intel(R) Celeron(R) G4930T CPU @ 3.>\n[2025-07-01 09:32:40,118] DEBUG ARM: system_info.get_cpu_info ARM64 output: <re.Match obj